WEBVTT

00:49.000 --> 00:53.291
[applause]

00:56.458 --> 00:59.291
Hi. I'm Jon.

01:01.125 --> 01:03.166
I'm a musical-theater writer.

01:03.250 --> 01:05.583
One of the last of my species.

01:05.666 --> 01:06.958
[laughter]

01:07.041 --> 01:10.916
Sorry. So… so, you know, lately,
I've been hearing this sound.

01:11.000 --> 01:12.291
[slow ticking]

01:12.375 --> 01:16.375
Everywhere I go,
like a tick, tick, tick…

01:16.458 --> 01:22.041
Like a time bomb in some cheesy B-movie
or Saturday morning cartoon.

01:22.125 --> 01:25.875
The fuse has been lit.
The clock counts down the seconds

01:25.958 --> 01:30.625
as the flame gets closer,
and closer, and closer,

01:30.708 --> 01:33.791
until… all at once…

01:33.875 --> 01:35.666
[boom]

01:37.666 --> 01:40.083
[mimicking trumpets]

01:40.166 --> 01:42.083
[laughs]

01:42.583 --> 01:45.666
[mimicking trumpets]

01:45.750 --> 01:48.333
[woman] This is Jonathan Larson's story.

01:48.416 --> 01:50.833
Happy anniversary, I love you so much.

01:51.708 --> 01:53.666
[woman] Before the Tony Awards.

01:54.458 --> 01:56.708
Before the Pulitzer Prize.

01:57.250 --> 01:58.250
Before…

01:58.333 --> 02:01.083
We dedicate this opening night
and every performance

02:01.166 --> 02:03.250
to our friend, Jonathan Larson.

02:03.333 --> 02:05.333
-[cheers]
-[woman] …we lost him.

02:07.125 --> 02:07.958
[both scream]

02:08.041 --> 02:11.000
[woman] Everything
you're about to see is true.

02:12.208 --> 02:14.583
Except for the parts Jonathan made up.

02:20.333 --> 02:23.333
[jovial tune playing]

02:23.416 --> 02:27.250
The date is January 26th, 1990.

02:27.333 --> 02:31.916
The setting, the barren,
unfashionable no-man's-land

02:32.000 --> 02:35.000
between SoHo and Greenwich Village.

02:35.083 --> 02:38.958
I have two keyboards,
a Macintosh computer.

02:39.041 --> 02:40.791
-A cat.
-[meows]

02:40.875 --> 02:43.666
An impressive collection of compact discs,

02:43.750 --> 02:46.541
cassettes, and records
of other people's music.

02:46.625 --> 02:51.958
Bookshelves sagging under the weight
of plays and novels I didn't write.

02:52.041 --> 02:55.750
I have an original,
dystopian rock musical…

02:55.833 --> 02:56.916
[tune stops]

02:57.000 --> 03:00.416
…that I have spent the last eight years
of my life writing…

03:00.500 --> 03:01.541
[deep breathing]

03:01.625 --> 03:04.833
-…and rewriting, and rewriting.
-[laughter]

03:04.916 --> 03:06.666
[moans]

03:07.208 --> 03:11.000
I have rejection letters
from every major and minor producer,

03:11.083 --> 03:14.583
theater company, record label,
and film studio in existence.

03:14.666 --> 03:16.333
And in just over a week…

03:19.291 --> 03:21.291
I will be 30 years old.

03:22.833 --> 03:26.166
Older than Stephen Sondheim
when he had his first Broadway show.

03:26.250 --> 03:30.916
Older than Paul McCartney when
he wrote his last song with John Lennon.

03:31.000 --> 03:34.916
By the time my parents were 30,
they already had two kids,

03:35.000 --> 03:36.250
they had careers

03:36.333 --> 03:38.708
with steady paychecks, a mortgage.

03:38.791 --> 03:43.541
And in eight days,
my youth will be over forever.

03:43.625 --> 03:46.041
And what exactly do I have
to show for myself?

03:47.166 --> 03:48.291
[sighs]

03:48.875 --> 03:50.708
Happy birthday!

03:51.416 --> 03:56.958
♪ Stop the clock ♪

03:57.041 --> 04:02.500
♪ Take time out ♪

04:02.583 --> 04:05.083
♪ Time to regroup ♪

04:05.166 --> 04:10.708
♪ Before you lose the bout ♪

04:10.791 --> 04:15.791
♪ Freeze the frame ♪

04:16.541 --> 04:21.875
♪ Back it up ♪

04:21.958 --> 04:24.458
♪ Time to refocus ♪

04:24.541 --> 04:29.416
♪ Before they wrap it up ♪

04:30.166 --> 04:32.500
♪ Years are getting shorter ♪

04:32.583 --> 04:35.541
♪ Lines on your face are getting longer ♪

04:35.625 --> 04:38.333
♪ Feel like you're treading water ♪

04:38.416 --> 04:41.000
♪ But the riptide's getting stronger ♪

04:41.083 --> 04:43.458
♪ Don't panic, don't jump ship ♪

04:43.541 --> 04:46.583
♪ Can't fight it, like taxes ♪

04:46.666 --> 04:51.458
♪ At least it happens
Only once in your life ♪

04:52.166 --> 04:54.708
♪ They're singing "Happy Birthday" ♪

04:54.791 --> 04:57.541
♪ You just want to lay down and cry ♪

04:57.625 --> 05:02.625
♪ Not just another birthday, it's 30/90 ♪

05:02.708 --> 05:05.125
♪ Why can't you stay 29? ♪

05:05.208 --> 05:08.500
♪ Hell, you still feel like you're 22 ♪

05:08.583 --> 05:10.916
♪ Turn 30, 1990 ♪

05:11.000 --> 05:15.625
♪ Bang! You're dead
What can you do? ♪

05:15.708 --> 05:20.041
♪ What can you do? ♪

05:21.000 --> 05:24.083
♪ What can you do? ♪

05:25.333 --> 05:26.833
I made ten copies.

05:27.333 --> 05:29.000
You are an angel on earth.

05:29.083 --> 05:32.291
-This is the last time. Seriously.
-I know. Thank you.

05:32.375 --> 05:33.958
-No, no, no, I got you.
-I'm gonna pay.

05:34.041 --> 05:36.916
-[Jon] I don't want you to pay.
-Somebody needs to take out this trash.

05:37.000 --> 05:39.125
So I hear you're moving
out of Jon's place.

05:39.208 --> 05:41.083
That's the end of an era.

05:41.166 --> 05:44.583
We hear him sobbing in the fridge
most mornings. It's very sad.

05:44.666 --> 05:47.041
[Jon] No, no, no.
We are not talking about that.

05:47.125 --> 05:49.375
Wait, Carolyn,
you're coming next Friday, right?

05:49.458 --> 05:50.583
What's happening Friday?

05:50.666 --> 05:53.583
-[both] The Superbia workshop.
-Surprised he hasn't mentioned it.

05:53.666 --> 05:54.916
That sounds vaguely familiar.

05:55.000 --> 05:58.083
Guys, this is the biggest break
I've ever had. This is that moment.

05:58.166 --> 06:01.875
It's the first time people are gonna
see the show that aren't just us.

06:01.958 --> 06:04.291
It's good you're not putting
too much pressure on it.

06:04.375 --> 06:06.500
-[all chuckling]
-[Jon] But it's true, though.

06:06.583 --> 06:11.083
It's like, you get to a certain age and
you stop being a writer who waits tables

06:11.166 --> 06:13.875
and you become a waiter with a hobby.

06:13.958 --> 06:16.083
Boo-Boo, you need to ask yourself,
in this moment,

06:16.166 --> 06:19.166
are you letting yourself
be led by fear or by love?

06:21.750 --> 06:23.000
[gasps]

06:23.083 --> 06:25.083
♪ Clear the runway ♪

06:25.166 --> 06:28.583
♪ Make another pass ♪

06:28.666 --> 06:30.833
♪ Try one more approach ♪

06:30.916 --> 06:33.541
♪ Before you're out of gas ♪

06:33.625 --> 06:35.958
♪ Friends are getting fatter ♪

06:36.041 --> 06:39.250
♪ Hairs on your head are getting thinner ♪

06:39.333 --> 06:41.958
♪ Feel like a cleanup batter ♪

06:42.041 --> 06:44.708
♪ On a team that ain't a winner ♪

06:44.791 --> 06:47.166
♪ Don't freak out, don't strike out ♪

06:47.250 --> 06:49.958
♪ Can't fight it, like City Hall ♪

06:50.041 --> 06:52.416
♪ At least you're not alone ♪

06:52.500 --> 06:55.583
♪ Your friends are there too ♪

06:55.666 --> 06:58.125
♪ And they're singing "Happy Birthday" ♪

06:58.208 --> 07:01.166
♪ You just wish you could run away ♪

07:01.250 --> 07:03.416
♪ Who cares about a birthday? ♪

07:03.500 --> 07:06.708
♪ But 30/90, hey ♪

07:06.791 --> 07:09.083
♪ Can you be optimistic? ♪

07:09.166 --> 07:11.958
♪ You're no longer the ingénue ♪

07:12.041 --> 07:14.458
♪ Turn 30, 1990 ♪

07:14.541 --> 07:16.166
♪ Boom! You're passé ♪

07:16.250 --> 07:19.291
♪ What can you do? ♪

07:19.375 --> 07:24.500
♪ What can you do? ♪

07:24.583 --> 07:28.291
♪ What can you do? ♪

07:28.375 --> 07:30.166
You just quit?

07:30.250 --> 07:33.458
Well, no, I didn't just "quit" quit.
I gave… I gave my notice.

07:33.541 --> 07:37.291
-That's exactly the same thing.
-No, I have two weeks left.

07:37.375 --> 07:40.625
I'm allowing myself to be led by love.

07:40.708 --> 07:41.708
What?

07:41.791 --> 07:44.125
You know, Rosa's got another client.
Craig Carnelia.

07:44.208 --> 07:46.916
This is Rosa your agent,
who hasn't returned your calls in a year?

07:47.000 --> 07:48.083
Yeah, yeah. That's the one.

07:48.166 --> 07:52.291
So she invited the entire theater industry
to Craig's musical workshop last year.

07:52.375 --> 07:54.250
And by intermission, some producer

07:54.333 --> 07:58.250
had already written him
a check for ten thousand dollars.

07:59.166 --> 08:01.666
I just wish that
you didn't have to think like that.

08:01.750 --> 08:03.500
Well, it's expensive to make art.

08:03.583 --> 08:05.541
No, baby, it's expensive to make art here.

08:05.625 --> 08:07.750
-Yeah, but worth every penny.
-[chuckles]

08:07.833 --> 08:10.291
-That's beautiful.
-I know, right?

08:10.375 --> 08:12.166
How are you gonna pay for this, Jonathan?

08:17.000 --> 08:19.458
♪ Peter Pan and Tinkerbell ♪

08:19.541 --> 08:22.625
♪ Which way to Never Never Land? ♪

08:22.708 --> 08:25.166
♪ Emerald City's gone to hell ♪

08:25.250 --> 08:28.416
-♪ Since the wizard blew off his command ♪
-♪ Blew off his command ♪

08:28.500 --> 08:31.083
♪ On the streets you hear the voices ♪

08:31.166 --> 08:33.625
♪ Lost children, crocodiles ♪

08:33.708 --> 08:35.083
♪ You're not into ♪

08:35.166 --> 08:37.625
♪ Making choices, wicked witches ♪

08:37.708 --> 08:40.375
♪ Poppy fields or men behind the curtain ♪

08:40.458 --> 08:43.000
♪ Tiger lilies, ruby slippers ♪

08:43.083 --> 08:45.958
♪ Clock is ticking, that's for certain ♪

08:46.041 --> 08:48.083
♪ They're singing "Happy Birthday" ♪

08:48.166 --> 08:51.375
-♪ Happy birthday ♪
-♪ I just wish it all were a dream ♪

08:51.458 --> 08:53.916
♪ It feels much more like doomsday ♪

08:54.000 --> 08:56.375
-♪ Fuck 30/90 ♪
-♪ 30/90 ♪

08:56.458 --> 08:59.291
♪ Seems like I'm in for a twister ♪

08:59.375 --> 09:02.250
♪ I don't see a rainbow, do you? ♪

09:02.333 --> 09:04.958
♪ Turn 30 in the '90s ♪

09:05.041 --> 09:07.583
♪ Look into my hands now
The ball has passed ♪

09:07.666 --> 09:10.041
♪ I want the spoils, but not too fast ♪

09:10.125 --> 09:12.875
♪ The world is calling
It's now or Neverland ♪

09:12.958 --> 09:15.666
♪ Why can't I stay a child forever and? ♪

09:15.750 --> 09:18.541
♪ 30/90, 30/90 ♪

09:18.625 --> 09:21.625
♪ 30/90, 30/90 ♪

09:21.708 --> 09:24.583
-♪ 30/90, 30, 30/90 ♪
-♪ 30, 30/90 ♪

09:24.666 --> 09:29.416
-♪ What can I do? ♪
-♪ What can I do? ♪

09:29.500 --> 09:33.916
♪ 30/90, 30, 30/90 ♪

09:34.000 --> 09:40.583
♪ What can I do? ♪

09:41.791 --> 09:45.458
[crowd cheering, clapping]

09:47.875 --> 09:50.541
Ladies and gentlemen,
please give it up for our band,

09:50.625 --> 09:53.375
and also for my
very, very, very dear friends,

09:54.333 --> 09:57.416
Roger and Karessa on vocals.

09:57.500 --> 09:59.291
[applause]

10:02.375 --> 10:03.500
Friday night.

10:03.583 --> 10:05.291
-[machine beeps]
-Hi, Jonathan, it's Deborah.

10:05.375 --> 10:07.625
Susan dropped off your music
for tonight's dance--

10:07.708 --> 10:10.166
-[tape rewinds]
-…but I can't get the speakers to work.

10:10.250 --> 10:11.666
[door opens]

10:12.666 --> 10:15.041
-Hey, Pookie.
-Hi.

10:15.125 --> 10:16.208
How was Philly?

10:16.291 --> 10:18.125
I went from the airport
to a conference room

10:18.208 --> 10:20.250
and then back to the airport
three hours later.

10:21.291 --> 10:22.500
-Sounds amazing.
-Mm.

10:22.583 --> 10:24.958
[Jon] Michael was an amazing actor.

10:25.875 --> 10:29.375
Yeah, he was the lead of every play
in high school, college.

10:29.458 --> 10:32.208
And then we moved to New York.

10:32.291 --> 10:35.000
I am sick of waking up at 5:00

10:35.083 --> 10:38.416
to get in line outside
the Equity Building and wait all day,

10:38.500 --> 10:41.208
praying that the director
actually even agrees

10:41.291 --> 10:43.500
to see anyone that's non-union, and then,

10:43.583 --> 10:46.166
when I finally do get in the room, I sing…

10:46.250 --> 10:49.291
I don't know, six measures,
if I'm lucky, before they cut me off

10:49.375 --> 10:50.708
and call me the wrong name--

10:50.791 --> 10:52.541
Juan, Pedro, Carlos… lo que sea.

10:52.625 --> 10:57.125
And then a week later, he got a job
at a fancy advertising company,

10:57.208 --> 11:00.333
making high five figures. [exhales]

11:00.416 --> 11:01.958
Healthcare, dental…

11:03.041 --> 11:04.375
He never looked back.

11:04.458 --> 11:06.250
You know, for someone who's broke,

11:06.333 --> 11:09.458
you could probably spend
a little bit less on party planning.

11:09.541 --> 11:11.833
[Jon] Well, what is the point of money,

11:11.916 --> 11:14.125
if you're not gonna spend it
on the people you love?

11:14.208 --> 11:16.666
-Yeah, except you don't have any money.
-Oh, right.

11:16.750 --> 11:18.875
This has been sitting here for a week.

11:18.958 --> 11:22.166
-I'm on it.
-Mm-hm. Yeah. You seem very on it.

11:22.250 --> 11:25.458
Pretty soon you won't have me around
to remind you to pay your bills on time.

11:25.541 --> 11:27.583
How will I ever survive?

11:27.666 --> 11:30.250
That's a very real question.
Have you found a new roommate yet?

11:31.000 --> 11:34.416
I've been a little busy. You know.
My workshop is next week.

11:34.500 --> 11:35.750
Wait, what workshop?

11:38.208 --> 11:39.791
[snickering]

11:39.875 --> 11:41.041
That was funny.

11:45.958 --> 11:47.708
[Michael] What time's the show tonight?

11:49.708 --> 11:50.833
Uh…

11:51.333 --> 11:53.083
-Curtain's at 8:00.
-[Michael] Mm…

11:53.666 --> 11:57.625
I've heard the dancing's amazing,
but the music sucks.

11:57.708 --> 12:00.166
[piano playing chords]

12:13.958 --> 12:16.208
[Jon] Susan grew up
in a small town in the Midwest.

12:16.291 --> 12:18.291
She went to college to study biology,

12:18.375 --> 12:20.500
she thought she'd become
a doctor, maybe teach.

12:20.583 --> 12:23.166
-But then she fell in love…
-[all gasping]

12:23.250 --> 12:26.333
-…with modern dance instead.
-[all exhale]

12:26.416 --> 12:29.250
-Every parent's dream, right?
-[faint laughter]

12:29.333 --> 12:31.958
She moved to New York
without knowing a soul.

12:32.041 --> 12:33.666
Four years later, she's already danced

12:33.750 --> 12:35.458
with every major choreographer
in the city.

12:35.541 --> 12:37.416
Paul, Trisha, Merce.

12:38.125 --> 12:42.583
1990. This was the year
she was finally gonna join a company.

12:42.666 --> 12:46.791
Not just go from job to job.
Actually have a home, an artistic family.

12:46.875 --> 12:50.500
And she was ready.
This was her year. She knew it.

12:50.583 --> 12:54.500
And then she fractured her ankle
during a dress rehearsal.

12:54.583 --> 12:57.083
[piano continues playing]

12:58.375 --> 13:03.083
[Jon] Six months of rehab later,
she's dancing again, it's just…

13:04.291 --> 13:09.000
whatever that moment was, when she knew…

13:09.083 --> 13:11.166
all of a sudden, she doesn't know anymore.

13:11.250 --> 13:12.083
[gasps]

13:12.166 --> 13:14.000
But Susan is a real artist.

13:14.083 --> 13:18.375
She doesn't care about seeing her name
in the New York Times.

13:18.458 --> 13:22.750
It doesn't matter to her
if she's dancing in front of five people

13:22.833 --> 13:24.833
or in front of five thousand.

13:24.916 --> 13:26.333
[slow ticking]

13:26.416 --> 13:28.458
And then there's the matter of us.

13:28.541 --> 13:31.041
[applause]

13:33.250 --> 13:34.583
Whoo!

13:35.083 --> 13:37.875
["Love Shack" by B-52s playing]

13:38.458 --> 13:41.291
♪ Love shack
Baby, love shack ♪

13:42.083 --> 13:45.041
♪ Love shack
Baby, love shack… ♪

13:49.958 --> 13:52.208
You know he can't
afford all of this, right?

13:52.291 --> 13:54.833
[indistinct chatter]

13:54.916 --> 13:57.958
Well, he loves making a fuss,
especially about you.

13:58.041 --> 13:59.291
Hm.

14:01.000 --> 14:02.500
["Love Shack" continues playing]

14:04.208 --> 14:06.375
After everything we've done for him…

14:06.458 --> 14:07.958
-[Jon] Stop!
-…he walks away.

14:08.041 --> 14:09.666
Freddy, look, I'm leaving you my mixtapes.

14:09.750 --> 14:12.375
-Oh!
-You can play them in remembrance of me.

14:12.458 --> 14:16.083
Jonathan Larson's famous
Moondance Diner mixtape.

14:16.166 --> 14:18.833
Who doesn't love showtunes
with their French toast?

14:18.916 --> 14:22.625
Actually, it's not just showtunes.
It's a very eclectic mix.

14:22.708 --> 14:24.875
-Someone's very touchy about mixtapes.
-Apparently.

14:24.958 --> 14:26.416
Okay, listen. I'm happy for you.

14:26.500 --> 14:27.916
-I really am.
-Oh, yeah?

14:28.000 --> 14:31.125
I'm also extremely bitter
and jealous and envious,

14:31.208 --> 14:33.791
and sort of hateful towards you right now.

14:33.875 --> 14:36.541
I mean… he's getting out.

14:37.166 --> 14:38.708
And you're gonna be next.

14:38.791 --> 14:41.666
-Well, I got a callback last week.
-Great!

14:41.750 --> 14:43.958
-For a cruise.
-What's wrong with a cruise?

14:44.041 --> 14:45.083
[snorts]

14:45.166 --> 14:48.250
It's an Arctic cruise,
so pretty much everything.

14:48.333 --> 14:52.083
Uh, every single thing is wrong with that.
It's in the Arctic.

14:52.708 --> 14:54.958
-How you feeling?
-Um…

14:55.041 --> 14:56.666
It's been a really good week.

14:56.750 --> 15:00.833
T-cell count is good.
My doctor feels cautiously optimistic.

15:00.916 --> 15:03.166
Okay, good. You look great.

15:03.250 --> 15:04.750
Oh, my God, thank you. I know.

15:04.833 --> 15:06.083
[chuckles softly]

15:06.166 --> 15:08.083
But for the cruise,
I'm gonna have to sort of…

15:08.166 --> 15:10.625
-Tighten up. Pull it, pull it up.
-Make it tight.

15:10.708 --> 15:14.041
Scott and I, we used to sing madrigals
in high school.

15:14.125 --> 15:16.208
-What? Really?
-[Scott] Yeah, yeah.

15:16.291 --> 15:19.083
I hated singing.
I just did it for the pussy. [laughs]

15:19.166 --> 15:24.250
Ran into Scott in SoHo and he really…
really wanted to come.

15:24.875 --> 15:25.791
Got it. Got it.

15:25.875 --> 15:28.291
I never get to go
to artist parties, you know?

15:28.375 --> 15:30.916
It sucks.
The drugs there are always the best.

15:31.000 --> 15:32.500
Mm. Mm-hm…

15:32.583 --> 15:34.833
-Scott's in finance.
-Shocking.

15:34.916 --> 15:38.375
-Yeah. What do you do?
-I'm the future of musical theater, Scott.

15:42.166 --> 15:45.208
Welcome. I'm gonna get another drink.

15:47.833 --> 15:49.625
That guy's hilarious.

15:50.375 --> 15:52.500
-[laughter]
-[glasses clinking]

15:53.833 --> 15:57.666
[tapping rhythmically]

15:59.458 --> 16:01.958
[others join in tapping a beat]

16:04.833 --> 16:07.666
♪ This is the life, bo-bo, bo-bo bo ♪

16:07.750 --> 16:10.500
♪ This is the life, bo-bo, bo-bo bo ♪

16:10.583 --> 16:13.375
♪ This is the life, bo-bo, bo-bo bo ♪

16:13.458 --> 16:16.500
♪ Bohemia ♪

16:16.583 --> 16:19.500
♪ Shower's in the kitchen
There might be some soap ♪

16:19.583 --> 16:22.583
♪ Dishes in the sink
Brush your teeth if you can cope ♪

16:22.666 --> 16:24.000
♪ Toilet's in the closet ♪

16:24.083 --> 16:27.041
♪ You better hope
There's a light bulb in there ♪

16:27.125 --> 16:28.291
Not today!

16:28.375 --> 16:31.166
♪ Revolving door roommates
Prick up your ears ♪

16:31.250 --> 16:34.083
-♪ Fourteen people in just four years ♪
-Whoo!

16:34.166 --> 16:37.125
♪ Ann and Max and Jonathan
And Carolyn and Kerri ♪

16:37.208 --> 16:39.166
♪ David, Tim--
No, Tim was just a guest from June ♪

16:39.250 --> 16:41.458
♪ To January
Margaret, Lisa, David, Susie ♪

16:41.541 --> 16:42.791
♪ Stephen, Joe and Sam ♪

16:42.875 --> 16:45.916
♪ And Elsa, the bill collector's dream
Who still is on the lam ♪

16:46.000 --> 16:48.833
♪ Don't forget the neighbors
Michelle and Gay ♪

16:48.916 --> 16:51.750
-[cheering]
-♪ More like a family than a family, hey ♪

16:51.833 --> 16:54.333
♪ The time is flying
And everything is dying ♪

16:54.416 --> 16:57.583
♪ I thought by now
I'd have a dog, a kid, a wife ♪

16:57.666 --> 17:00.708
♪ The ship is sort of sinking
So let's start drinking ♪

17:00.791 --> 17:03.208
♪ Before we start thinking
Is this the life? ♪

17:03.291 --> 17:06.291
-Yeah!
-♪ This is the life, bo-bo, bo-bo bo ♪

17:06.375 --> 17:09.416
♪ This is the life, bo-bo, bo-bo bo ♪

17:09.500 --> 17:12.375
♪ This is the life, bo-bo, bo-bo bo ♪

17:12.458 --> 17:15.375
-♪ Bohemia ♪
-♪ Yeah, yeah, yeah! ♪

17:15.458 --> 17:18.458
-♪ Bohemia ♪
-One more time!

17:18.541 --> 17:23.166
♪ Bohemia ♪

17:23.250 --> 17:24.500
♪ Bo-bo, bo-bo bo ♪

17:24.583 --> 17:27.958
[all shout and cheer]

17:28.041 --> 17:29.958
-Whoo!
-[cheering and clapping]

17:30.041 --> 17:31.541
[laughing]

17:32.250 --> 17:33.875
That was freaking amazing!

17:34.833 --> 17:36.541
-Whoo!
-Yeah, Scott!

17:37.333 --> 17:38.375
Whoa.

17:41.375 --> 17:44.250
Hi. Everyone's leaving.

17:44.333 --> 17:46.958
-I just needed some fresh air.
-Okay.

17:47.041 --> 17:48.833
It's freezing up here.

17:48.916 --> 17:49.750
[Jon shuddering]

17:49.833 --> 17:51.000
Where is your coat?

17:51.083 --> 17:53.375
Oh, I don't know. It's, uh…

17:54.250 --> 17:55.916
It's at the bottom of a very large pile.

17:56.000 --> 17:57.125
Oh!

17:57.208 --> 17:58.500
Mm.

17:59.291 --> 18:01.125
[sighing deeply]

18:03.708 --> 18:05.791
[Jon] Wow. That's pretty.

18:06.375 --> 18:07.875
That's the prison barge.

18:09.208 --> 18:11.750
-Oh, yeah.
-[both laugh]

18:13.041 --> 18:17.833
I heard, uh, in Jacob's Pillow, they're
hiring new teachers for the dance school.

18:18.875 --> 18:20.416
-Oh, yeah?
-Yeah.

18:20.500 --> 18:24.166
Work a couple of hours a week.
Then the rest of the time is yours.

18:24.250 --> 18:27.166
-Free studio space whenever you want.
-Hey… Whoa…

18:27.250 --> 18:29.208
-Can we just talk for a second?
-Mm.

18:29.291 --> 18:32.000
Can we just talk about
how amazing you were tonight?

18:34.250 --> 18:37.125
-Thank you.
-I am not messing around.

18:37.208 --> 18:39.708
I could just watch you dancing forever.

18:44.708 --> 18:46.500
I was thinking of maybe applying.

18:46.583 --> 18:49.208
-Hm?
-To the job in Jacob's Pillow.

18:49.958 --> 18:52.500
-We went there last summer, remember?
-Oh.

18:52.583 --> 18:53.833
We saw the new Mark Morris.

18:53.916 --> 18:55.458
-Oh, yeah!
-Yeah.

18:56.583 --> 18:58.666
-That's the place in the Berkshires?
-Mm-hm.

18:58.750 --> 19:01.916
So, you're gonna move to the Berkshires?

19:02.000 --> 19:05.041
And not have to work
30 hours a week doing word processing

19:05.125 --> 19:07.208
to pay the rent, why not?

19:07.291 --> 19:09.708
I might actually be able
to get back into shape.

19:10.750 --> 19:13.875
Okay. Yeah. All right.
Let's do it. Let's move.

19:15.625 --> 19:17.875
-I'm being serious.
-Hey, I'm being serious.

19:17.958 --> 19:21.375
We're gonna live in a log cabin.
We're gonna hunt… acorns.

19:21.458 --> 19:24.708
We're gonna-- [spluttering]
We're gonna gather squirrels.

19:24.791 --> 19:27.500
[laughing]
What are you even talking about?

19:27.583 --> 19:29.458
-[laughs]
-It's the Berkshires.

19:29.541 --> 19:32.208
People have vacation homes there.
You've been there.

19:32.875 --> 19:35.666
I'm so sorry.
Can we-- Can we please go inside?

19:35.750 --> 19:37.291
Sorry, I just feel like I'm scared--

19:37.375 --> 19:39.541
I'm beginning
to lose sensation in my extremities.

19:39.625 --> 19:41.166
You are such a baby.

19:41.750 --> 19:43.125
Take this.

19:45.791 --> 19:47.541
[Jon] Whoa. Hold on.

19:48.958 --> 19:51.291
-[exhales deeply]
-You like?

19:54.666 --> 19:57.333
I thought that you were in a hurry
to get back inside.

20:01.500 --> 20:03.625
[R&B music playing loudly]

20:05.708 --> 20:08.500
-[muffled music]
-[moans through wall]

20:13.875 --> 20:16.458
You know that job in the Berkshires?

20:16.541 --> 20:19.416
-Yeah, sounds amazing.
-I already applied for it.

20:19.500 --> 20:20.958
-Oh, yeah?
-Yeah.

20:21.041 --> 20:22.958
-And I got it.
-Oh…

20:23.541 --> 20:25.333
-Oh, yeah? That's great.
-Yeah.

20:26.500 --> 20:28.375
It starts in June.

20:28.458 --> 20:30.625
Okay. So this is just for the summer?

20:30.708 --> 20:32.541
No. Mm-mm, it's permanent.

20:36.083 --> 20:37.125
Jon?

20:38.166 --> 20:41.000
Whoa, the Berkshires?

20:41.083 --> 20:44.791
That is, like, so far from Midtown.

20:44.875 --> 20:46.541
[pained chuckle] Yeah. Yeah.

20:46.625 --> 20:48.541
Why is she doing this right now?

20:48.625 --> 20:51.041
And she says,
"I want you to come with me."

20:51.125 --> 20:54.083
-What did you say?
-I said, "Oh?"

20:54.166 --> 20:56.583
[laughs]

20:57.166 --> 20:59.833
What am I supposed to say?
I didn't know what to say.

20:59.916 --> 21:02.666
I mean, like, I can't…
I can't leave New York.

21:02.750 --> 21:05.000
-Oh, tell her to move in with you.
-Move in where?

21:05.083 --> 21:06.583
You need a new roommate, right?

21:06.666 --> 21:09.625
It's two birds, one stone.
You are very welcome.

21:10.416 --> 21:13.625
Okay, so, what… what about the guy
that you were dating? David?

21:13.708 --> 21:16.500
-I thought you guys were great together.
-It didn't work out.

21:18.291 --> 21:20.458
Oh. There's a focus group
at the office this week,

21:20.541 --> 21:23.583
and they're looking for a few more people.
How about I sign you up?

21:24.750 --> 21:27.333
So you can lure me to the dark side?

21:27.416 --> 21:30.000
No! So I can introduce you
to my colleagues,

21:30.083 --> 21:32.000
and show them how brilliant you are.

21:32.083 --> 21:33.500
I don't want a job in advertising.

21:33.583 --> 21:35.541
I don't want you
to have a job in advertising.

21:35.625 --> 21:38.666
I want you to have a job in…
jingle writing.

21:40.333 --> 21:41.625
-[laughs]
-No, listen.

21:41.708 --> 21:44.250
You come up with jingles
all the time for fun, Jon.

21:44.333 --> 21:46.375
You come up with songs
about cereal we're eating.

21:46.458 --> 21:48.500
-[sighs]
-You could get paid for that.

21:48.583 --> 21:51.291
Well, you know,
when Superbia gets produced,

21:51.375 --> 21:54.708
I will be getting paid
for my music anyway. So…

21:55.333 --> 21:56.583
That's true.

21:59.708 --> 22:03.541
[Michael] And we are here.
Home sweet home.

22:08.125 --> 22:09.583
[engine stops]

22:09.666 --> 22:13.875
Oh… my… God!

22:15.458 --> 22:19.125
Michael tosses the keys
to the parking attendant.

22:19.666 --> 22:20.666
[Michael chuckles]

22:20.750 --> 22:23.500
What apartment building
has a parking attendant?

22:23.583 --> 22:24.416
[laughter]

22:24.500 --> 22:26.208
[up-tempo rock music playing]

22:26.291 --> 22:28.250
[Jon] Fresh flowers in the lobby.

22:28.333 --> 22:31.625
An old, white lady with a tiny dog.

22:32.083 --> 22:33.916
Is this real life?

22:34.625 --> 22:37.208
♪ No more
Walking 13 blocks ♪

22:37.291 --> 22:39.416
♪ With 30 pounds of laundry ♪

22:39.500 --> 22:41.791
♪ In the freezing dead of winter ♪

22:44.208 --> 22:47.791
♪ No more
Walking up six flights of stairs ♪

22:47.875 --> 22:52.083
♪ Or throwing down the key
Because there is no buzzer ♪

22:54.291 --> 22:56.833
♪ No more faulty wiring ♪

22:56.916 --> 22:59.041
♪ No more crooked floors ♪

22:59.125 --> 23:02.666
♪ No more spitting out my Ultra Brite ♪

23:02.750 --> 23:04.833
♪ On top of dirty dishes ♪

23:04.916 --> 23:09.208
♪ In the one and only sink ♪

23:10.416 --> 23:14.666
-[mellow tune plays]
-♪ Hello to my walk-in closets ♪

23:14.750 --> 23:18.791
♪ Tidy as Park Avenue ♪

23:19.458 --> 23:23.500
♪ Hello, my butcher block table ♪

23:23.583 --> 23:25.625
♪ I could get used ♪

23:25.708 --> 23:27.750
♪ I could get used ♪

23:27.833 --> 23:30.791
♪ I could get used to you ♪

23:31.291 --> 23:34.416
[up-tempo rock music playing]

23:34.500 --> 23:38.375
♪ No more
Climbing over sleeping people ♪

23:38.458 --> 23:40.625
♪ Before you get out the door ♪

23:40.708 --> 23:42.666
♪ Of your own building ♪

23:44.291 --> 23:45.708
♪ No more ♪

23:45.791 --> 23:49.416
♪ Noxious fumes from gas heaters
That are illegal ♪

23:49.500 --> 23:52.958
♪ Or will blow up
While you are sleeping! ♪

23:54.500 --> 23:56.958
-♪ No more ♪
-♪ Leaky ceilings ♪

23:57.041 --> 23:59.708
-♪ No more ♪
-♪ Holes in the floor ♪

23:59.791 --> 24:02.625
♪ No more
Taking a shower in the kitchen ♪

24:02.708 --> 24:05.083
♪ While your roommate's
Eating breakfast ♪

24:05.166 --> 24:09.083
♪ And you're getting water
On his cornflakes ♪

24:09.166 --> 24:10.208
[mellow tune plays]

24:10.291 --> 24:14.875
♪ Hello to shiny
New parquet wood floors ♪

24:14.958 --> 24:19.208
♪ As waxed as a wealthy girl's legs ♪

24:19.291 --> 24:23.500
♪ Hello, dear Mr. Dishwasher ♪

24:23.583 --> 24:25.875
-♪ I could get used ♪
-♪ I could get used ♪

24:25.958 --> 24:28.166
-♪ I could get used ♪
-♪ I could get ♪

24:28.250 --> 24:32.208
-♪ Used to you ♪
-♪ I could get used to you ♪

24:32.291 --> 24:34.958
-[up-tempo rock music playing]
-♪ No more… exotic ♪

24:35.041 --> 24:37.333
♪ No more… neurotic ♪

24:37.416 --> 24:41.583
♪ No more anything
But pleasantly robotic ♪

24:41.666 --> 24:44.125
-♪ We're movin' on up ♪
-♪ We're movin' on up ♪

24:44.208 --> 24:46.708
-♪ To the East Side ♪
-♪ To the East Side ♪

24:46.791 --> 24:53.791
♪ To a deluxe apartment
In the sky ♪

24:55.125 --> 24:57.791
[music tempo slows]

24:57.875 --> 25:01.916
♪ Hello to dear Mr. Doorman ♪

25:02.000 --> 25:05.958
♪ Who looks like Captain Kangaroo ♪

25:06.041 --> 25:10.250
♪ Hello dear fellow, and how do you do? ♪

25:10.333 --> 25:12.208
-♪ I could get used ♪
-♪ I could get used ♪

25:12.291 --> 25:14.333
-♪ I could get used ♪
-♪ I could get ♪

25:14.416 --> 25:18.375
-♪ Used to you ♪
-♪ I could get used to you, yeah! ♪

25:18.458 --> 25:20.208
-♪ I could get used ♪
-♪ I could get used ♪

25:20.291 --> 25:22.500
-♪ Even seduced ♪
-♪ Even seduced ♪

25:22.583 --> 25:26.291
-♪ I could get used to you ♪
-♪ Used to you ♪

25:26.375 --> 25:27.791
Ow!

25:31.208 --> 25:32.708
-[song ends]
-[bell dings]

25:32.791 --> 25:34.666
[man over PA] Stand clear
of the closing doors.

25:34.750 --> 25:36.666
I swear to God!
I'm talking to you in the back.

25:36.750 --> 25:38.708
Stand clear of the closing doors.

25:39.708 --> 25:41.916
[man] You still don't have the song?

25:42.000 --> 25:45.041
[Jon] This has never happened
to me before. I… [sighs]

25:45.125 --> 25:47.625
I don't know.
I usually write a song in a day.

25:47.708 --> 25:50.916
Last week, I wrote a song about sugar.
It took me three hours.

25:51.000 --> 25:53.000
-Song about sugar?
-♪ Sugar ♪

25:53.083 --> 25:55.458
♪ She is refined
For a small price ♪

25:55.541 --> 25:57.541
♪ She blows my mind ♪

25:57.625 --> 25:59.208
Why would you do that?

25:59.291 --> 26:00.666
An exercise.

26:01.166 --> 26:02.166
In what?

26:02.250 --> 26:04.208
I like to see
if I can write a song about anything.

26:05.125 --> 26:08.166
Why don't you try to see
if you can write a song for your musical

26:08.250 --> 26:11.166
that's being presented
to an audience in six days instead?

26:11.250 --> 26:14.958
[Jon] Ira Weitzman, head of
musical theater at Playwrights Horizons.

26:15.041 --> 26:18.750
The first, and so far,
only actual theater person

26:18.833 --> 26:21.541
to offer to put on a workshop of Superbia.

26:21.625 --> 26:25.166
I'm starting to think
that maybe I don't need it.

26:25.875 --> 26:29.000
-You do need it.
-You know… [crunching]

26:29.083 --> 26:31.208
…you're the only person
who ever said that.

26:31.291 --> 26:32.375
Just so you know.

26:32.458 --> 26:35.708
You're telling me in the five years
you've been writing this musical…

26:35.791 --> 26:37.083
Eight years, actually.

26:37.166 --> 26:39.708
…no one else has told you
that you're missing a song

26:39.791 --> 26:41.208
for Elizabeth in the second act?

26:43.625 --> 26:44.458
No one.

26:46.875 --> 26:48.208
[Jon] Okay, I'm lying.

26:50.791 --> 26:53.541
[sighs] One person did say that.

27:01.958 --> 27:06.500
[Jon] For years, I was a part
of this musical theater writing workshop.

27:08.916 --> 27:15.333
♪ Liquid crystal digital readout ♪

27:15.416 --> 27:19.666
♪ Floating on a sea of gray ♪

27:19.750 --> 27:26.041
[Jon] Once a week, we would gather the few
surviving members of our dwindling tribe.

27:26.125 --> 27:31.041
We'd watch one of us present what
we'd been working on to a panel of, well…

27:32.083 --> 27:33.666
real writers.

27:34.833 --> 27:38.208
The theater legends,
who created the Broadway shows

27:38.291 --> 27:42.541
that we'd grown up dragging our parents
into the city to see…

27:42.625 --> 27:46.333
♪ Dividing the day away ♪

27:46.416 --> 27:49.375
[Jon] The panel would change every week.

27:49.458 --> 27:52.666
♪ Counting slowly ♪

27:52.750 --> 27:55.833
♪ Measuring moments… ♪

27:56.416 --> 27:59.041
[Jon] The night I presented,
people began to buzz

27:59.125 --> 28:01.416
as soon as we walked through the door.

28:02.291 --> 28:03.875
Is it really him?

28:05.166 --> 28:06.833
It was.

28:08.291 --> 28:12.208
Stephen Sondheim.

28:15.875 --> 28:18.250
-[laughter]
-[man] All right, I'll start.

28:19.708 --> 28:20.708
I'm lost.

28:21.708 --> 28:23.625
I… I don't know what the show is.

28:23.708 --> 28:26.458
Is it social commentary?
Is it science fiction?

28:26.541 --> 28:30.458
And the music is the same thing.
Is it rock? Is it Broadway? Is it both?

28:30.541 --> 28:33.166
Is it neither? Steve, what did you think?

28:36.500 --> 28:39.583
I have to say,
I disagree pretty strongly, Walter.

28:39.666 --> 28:42.791
I think this is a musical
that knows exactly what it is.

28:44.666 --> 28:46.958
Yes. Yes. Of course, yes. Abso--

28:47.041 --> 28:50.291
The world that you've created
is really original.

28:50.375 --> 28:51.958
It's fascinating.

28:52.041 --> 28:57.208
The problem is, it's not particularly easy
to follow the emotional thread.

28:57.291 --> 29:01.583
The details distract us
from connecting with the characters.

29:01.666 --> 29:03.333
-Does that make sense?
-Okay. Okay.

29:03.416 --> 29:06.416
Yes, yes. We're on the same page.
That's exactly how I felt.

29:06.500 --> 29:09.416
We're saying the same thing,
just differently.

29:09.500 --> 29:12.875
But the music, okay, I'm sorry--
The music just wasn't there.

29:12.958 --> 29:15.208
I actually--
I thought the songs were swell.

29:15.791 --> 29:19.500
Yeah, okay… Yes. Yes.
The individual songs.

29:19.583 --> 29:24.000
I particularly like the one the young man
sings at the end of the first act.

29:24.083 --> 29:27.416
First rate lyric and tune. Well done.

29:29.333 --> 29:32.208
[Jon] "First rate lyric and tune."

29:32.291 --> 29:33.291
Thank you.

29:33.375 --> 29:38.708
Those five words were enough
to keep me going for the next two years.

29:40.833 --> 29:44.625
You're missing a song
for the young woman. Uh…

29:44.708 --> 29:46.208
-Elizabeth?
-Elizabeth.

29:46.291 --> 29:48.458
It's the turning point in the show.

29:48.541 --> 29:51.750
Your protagonist is either gonna go
in this direction or that direction.

29:51.833 --> 29:55.625
Someone has to wake him up,
shake some sense into him.

29:56.208 --> 29:57.333
Okay.

29:57.416 --> 30:02.125
[laughing] It's so funny because I was
gonna say the exact same thing.

30:02.833 --> 30:06.583
Can we talk musicians?
Because if it's only gonna be four,

30:06.666 --> 30:10.291
then I gotta figure out how
I'm gonna split up the bass parts.

30:10.375 --> 30:11.916
This is for you. Here you go.

30:12.000 --> 30:13.416
-Thank you.
-Yeah. Uh…

30:13.500 --> 30:15.666
-Jon, this is a reading.
-Mm.

30:15.750 --> 30:16.916
You'll have a piano.

30:17.875 --> 30:19.375
I wrote a rock score.

30:19.458 --> 30:23.833
So, at the very least I'll need a synth
and drums and a guitar and--

30:23.916 --> 30:28.125
A great song should sound great
without any instruments.

30:28.208 --> 30:29.500
Mm. Okay.

30:29.583 --> 30:31.166
Let's just do the song as a cappella.

30:31.958 --> 30:34.500
Oh, actually, you know what?
Maybe we'll just skip the songs,

30:34.583 --> 30:37.666
and then we can get the audience
in and out in half an hour.

30:37.750 --> 30:39.416
I will take a look at the budget

30:39.500 --> 30:43.000
and I will see if I can dig up
some money for another musician.

30:43.083 --> 30:44.125
Two more.

30:44.625 --> 30:46.916
And piano is the absolute
bare minimum for this.

30:48.000 --> 30:49.250
Have you spoken to Rosa?

30:51.125 --> 30:55.583
Hey, Rosa, this is Jonathan Larson,
your client.

30:55.666 --> 30:58.208
I've left multiple messages
with your secretary.

30:58.291 --> 31:01.541
-Rosa Stevens is still your agent, right?
-Oh, yeah. No, yeah, we…

31:01.625 --> 31:02.625
We talk constantly.

31:02.708 --> 31:05.833
Has she sent out the invites
for the presentation yet?

31:05.916 --> 31:07.958
We haven't gotten a lot of RSVPs.

31:10.125 --> 31:11.500
-It's fine.
-Mm.

31:11.583 --> 31:14.791
Nobody has more contacts
in the industry than Rosa.

31:14.875 --> 31:17.625
I'm sure she'll get some
good people there for you.

31:18.375 --> 31:19.500
Yeah, yeah.

31:21.541 --> 31:23.375
-I'll see you Monday.
-Yes, sir.

31:24.166 --> 31:25.541
First day of rehearsal.

31:26.791 --> 31:29.708
And finish the song already. Please.

31:30.750 --> 31:32.375
-Thank you, Ira.
-Thanks.

31:32.458 --> 31:34.375
Thank you for all this. Thank you.

31:34.458 --> 31:35.875
[entry bell chimes]

31:37.250 --> 31:38.500
[door shuts]

31:39.125 --> 31:42.125
[slow, quiet ticking]

31:44.416 --> 31:46.666
[ticking intensifies]

31:49.708 --> 31:51.875
Yeah. I want to leave a message
for Mr. Sondheim.

31:51.958 --> 31:54.083
This is, um… my name is Jonathan Larson.

31:54.166 --> 31:56.291
Hi there, this is a message for Joe Papp.

31:56.375 --> 31:57.250
For Bernie Gersten.

31:57.333 --> 31:59.625
For the Artistic Director
of the Shubert Organization.

31:59.708 --> 32:03.416
For La MaMa. So, it's Larson, L-A-R-S-O-N.

32:03.500 --> 32:06.125
No, not Parson. It's something
that's never been done before.

32:06.208 --> 32:07.458
It's gonna be quite the event.

32:07.541 --> 32:11.041
It has tremendous commercial possibility.

32:11.125 --> 32:13.666
We're filling up fast.
I want to make sure you got your spot.

32:13.750 --> 32:17.041
I know that his time is limited.
Oh! It would be such a treat!

32:17.125 --> 32:19.708
Zero pressure.
Ha-ha. I really want you there.

32:19.791 --> 32:22.125
So, can I count you in?
There'll be a seat reserved for him.

32:22.208 --> 32:24.583
Superbia at Playwrights Horizons.
It's at 10:00 a.m.

32:24.666 --> 32:27.333
This Friday at 10:00 a.m.
I'm so excited about Friday.

32:27.416 --> 32:31.000
I wouldn't want you to miss it.
That's all the information I can give you.

32:31.083 --> 32:33.583
-[hangs up phone]
-[exhales deeply]

32:41.500 --> 32:44.583
["Sunday in the Park with George"
playing on TV]

32:44.666 --> 32:46.041
[man] ♪ Order! ♪

32:48.583 --> 32:51.541
[Michael] They should put
every Sondheim musical on PBS.

