♪ Never in the history
Of entertainment will there be an affair ♪

50:52.583 --> 50:54.083
Make sure you're not speeding up.

50:54.750 --> 50:56.166
♪ Quite like it ♪

50:56.250 --> 50:58.750
♪ The event of the century ♪

50:58.833 --> 51:01.083
♪ The quintessential social adventure… ♪

51:01.166 --> 51:04.208
I'm missing consonants
in "quintessential social adventure."

51:05.416 --> 51:07.250
-Hi. Thanks.
-It sounds great.

51:07.333 --> 51:09.333
Why didn't you tell me you were coming?

51:09.416 --> 51:12.291
-I thought it might be a nice surprise.
-Oh, no. It is. It is.

51:12.375 --> 51:13.875
Okay. It's Tuesday.

51:16.083 --> 51:17.541
Mm…

51:17.625 --> 51:21.291
I need to give them the decision
about the job by tomorrow, so…

51:21.375 --> 51:24.291
Is there a moment
where you can take a break?

51:25.125 --> 51:29.041
I can't. No, the actors take breaks.
I don't… I don't have any breaks.

51:29.125 --> 51:31.708
I just don't know what I'm gonna do. So…

51:31.791 --> 51:33.041
Um…

51:33.125 --> 51:35.041
Can you… Can you ask for an extension?

51:36.041 --> 51:39.250
I'm sorry, can we…
Can we talk about this tonight?

51:39.333 --> 51:41.333
I'm so… One second.

51:41.416 --> 51:43.583
This is… Can we get this section…

51:43.666 --> 51:46.166
♪ …there ♪

51:46.250 --> 51:48.750
[whispers, unintelligible]

51:54.375 --> 51:57.375
[drums join piano]

51:57.458 --> 51:59.208
-♪ A nomination ♪
-♪ A nomination? ♪

51:59.291 --> 52:01.250
♪ A nomination for a Face Award ♪

52:01.333 --> 52:04.083
-♪ A Face Award ♪
-♪ Let's plug in ♪

52:04.166 --> 52:05.958
♪ Does this mean
That I'll be on the air? ♪

52:06.041 --> 52:07.166
♪ You already were ♪

52:07.250 --> 52:09.458
-♪ Last night, what a sight you were ♪
-♪ I was? ♪

52:09.541 --> 52:11.416
♪ You were
You played with my laser ♪

52:11.500 --> 52:13.083
♪ You thought it was a razor ♪

52:13.166 --> 52:16.375
♪ I'm positive that's what
Caused such a scene ♪

52:16.458 --> 52:20.000
♪ We can get on the air
My music box on the air ♪

52:20.083 --> 52:22.708
♪ Where? Who?
What does this mean? ♪

52:22.791 --> 52:27.875
♪ Everyone who ever has
Or ever will be anyone will be there ♪

52:27.958 --> 52:29.625
[music fades]

52:29.708 --> 52:33.791
-[sighs nervously]
-I can give you 50 for everything.

52:34.875 --> 52:37.291
You're gonna sell it
for five times that amount.

52:37.375 --> 52:38.791
Fifty's the best I can do.

52:38.875 --> 52:40.208
[sighs]

52:43.125 --> 52:45.125
-Cash?
-Great.

52:49.083 --> 52:52.083
[sarcastic] Oh, no.
He's keeping the Godspell.

52:53.125 --> 52:54.708
"Day by Day."

52:54.791 --> 52:56.083
[music continues]

52:56.166 --> 52:58.000
Yeah, yeah. I love it.

52:58.083 --> 52:59.583
Ah, ah, ah!

52:59.666 --> 53:04.083
[Michael] I'd love to take you to lunch.
Celebrate your birthday.

53:04.166 --> 53:05.458
I can't this week.

53:06.625 --> 53:09.500
I could really use
your advice on some things.

53:09.583 --> 53:12.250
Hey, Michael? I'm sorry,
can I call you back later?

53:12.333 --> 53:15.041
I'm just… I'm right in the middle
of something here.

53:15.833 --> 53:18.125
Oh, uh, that focus group I mentioned…

53:19.125 --> 53:21.333
They're still looking
for one more person to sign up.

53:21.416 --> 53:24.125
It's Thursday at 11:00.
I know money's tight for you right now.

53:24.208 --> 53:25.625
You know what? Never mind.

53:25.708 --> 53:28.416
Uh, wait. How much does it pay?

53:28.500 --> 53:31.500
It's only 75 bucks,
but it could be a thing.

53:34.583 --> 53:35.500
I'll be there.

53:35.583 --> 53:37.916
Thank you really. That's… Yeah, thank you.

53:38.000 --> 53:40.416
-Wow.
-Okay, bye. Bye-bye.

53:40.500 --> 53:41.833
All right, see you.

53:52.458 --> 53:54.333
[music builds]

53:56.083 --> 53:58.166
[full rock band plays]

53:58.250 --> 54:02.166
♪ Everyone who ever has
Or ever will be anyone will be there ♪

54:02.250 --> 54:04.291
-You were right.
-I know.

54:04.375 --> 54:07.500
♪ Never in the history
Of entertainment will there be ♪

54:07.583 --> 54:11.083
♪ An affair quite like it ♪

54:11.166 --> 54:13.708
♪ The event of the century ♪

54:13.791 --> 54:16.208
♪ The quintessential social adventure ♪

54:16.291 --> 54:20.000
♪ We cannot afford to miss
This night of bliss ♪

54:20.083 --> 54:22.541
♪ The 31st annual Face Awards ♪

54:22.625 --> 54:26.041
♪ Presentation ceremony
Live via satellite in color ♪

54:26.125 --> 54:29.250
♪ It's an 18-hour function
With commercial interruption ♪

54:29.333 --> 54:32.791
♪ From a marvelous, glorious
Slam bang glamorama ♪

54:32.875 --> 54:36.000
♪ Everyone who's anyone knows
Everyone who's anyone knows ♪

54:36.083 --> 54:39.291
♪ Everyone who's anyone knows
Everyone who's anyone knows ♪

54:39.375 --> 54:42.791
♪ Everyone who's anyone knows
Everyone will be ♪

54:42.875 --> 54:47.958
♪ There ♪

54:48.041 --> 54:49.750
[music ends]

54:54.000 --> 54:55.375
[sighs]

54:56.000 --> 54:57.958
-Can I hear it?
-[laughs nervously]

54:58.041 --> 54:59.958
-Huh?
-The new song.

55:02.166 --> 55:05.125
-Any day now.
-[light chuckle]

55:05.208 --> 55:07.916
-You're killin' me, Larson.
-[strained laugh]

55:10.375 --> 55:12.916
[playing gentle tune]

55:17.375 --> 55:19.333
-[phone rings]
-Oh, sh…

55:19.958 --> 55:21.208
Shh!

55:24.083 --> 55:26.750
-[phone continues ringing]
-My God.

55:28.625 --> 55:30.416
[answering machine] ♪ Speak ♪

55:30.500 --> 55:31.958
[beep]

55:32.458 --> 55:35.375
[Susan] Hey, it's me.
Just pick up the phone.

55:35.458 --> 55:37.916
I know you're screening your calls.

55:38.000 --> 55:40.833
Every light is on
in your apartment right now.

55:47.833 --> 55:49.125
I can see you!

55:52.125 --> 55:53.166
[sighs]

55:55.916 --> 55:58.875
Hey. Hi. You could have called first.

55:58.958 --> 56:00.750
-I just did.
-Mm.

56:00.833 --> 56:02.333
It's good to see you too.

56:02.916 --> 56:04.416
[exhales]

56:05.625 --> 56:08.208
[Jon] I didn't mean it like that.

56:09.416 --> 56:11.541
-Jesus, Jonathan.
-[sighs]

56:11.625 --> 56:13.250
I need you to talk to me.

56:14.083 --> 56:15.708
I'm writing, Susan. I'm writing.

56:15.791 --> 56:18.916
You're gonna write a great
American musical in the next ten minutes?

56:19.000 --> 56:21.000
Thank you for being
so supportive of my work.

56:21.083 --> 56:24.166
[scoffs] Because you've been
such a champion of mine?

56:24.250 --> 56:26.500
-What's that supposed to mean?
-What do you think it means?

56:28.375 --> 56:32.250
And now, ladies and gentlemen,
we present you with…

56:32.333 --> 56:33.250
[drum roll]

56:33.333 --> 56:39.375
…scenes from a modern
romance as told in song.

56:47.083 --> 56:48.625
I'm sorry, I'm sorry. I--

56:48.708 --> 56:51.958
I'm not allowed to talk about my needs.
What needs?

56:52.041 --> 56:54.791
-Did I say that?
-You didn't have to say it. It's implied.

56:54.875 --> 56:56.500
How is it implied?

56:56.583 --> 57:00.791
You're the artist and I'm the girlfriend.
That's how you feel, right?

57:00.875 --> 57:05.875
♪ I feel bad
That you feel bad ♪

57:05.958 --> 57:11.333
♪ About me feeling bad
About you feeling bad ♪

57:11.416 --> 57:16.750
♪ About what I said
About what you said ♪

57:16.833 --> 57:20.666
♪ About me not being able ♪

57:20.750 --> 57:27.750
♪ To share a feeling ♪

57:27.833 --> 57:31.791
-Can we talk about this later, please?
-When, Jonathan? When is later?

57:32.375 --> 57:34.125
Not tonight.

57:35.583 --> 57:39.291
♪ If I thought that
What you thought ♪

57:39.375 --> 57:43.958
♪ Was that I hadn't thought
About sharing my thoughts ♪

57:44.041 --> 57:48.125
♪ Then my reaction
To your reaction ♪

57:48.208 --> 57:54.416
♪ To my reaction
Would have been more revealing ♪

57:54.500 --> 57:58.041
I have been rehearsing all day.
I have been up since four this morning.

57:58.125 --> 58:02.875
I have been trying to write a song
for a week and I am nowhere.

58:02.958 --> 58:04.958
♪ I was afraid that you'd be afraid ♪

58:05.041 --> 58:08.750
♪ If I told you that
I was afraid of intimacy ♪

58:08.833 --> 58:11.833
I've been telling you
how unhappy I am for months.

58:11.916 --> 58:14.708
♪ If you don't have a problem
With my problem ♪

58:14.791 --> 58:18.125
♪ Maybe the problem's
Simply co-dependency ♪

58:18.208 --> 58:22.416
Everyone's unhappy in New York!
That's what New York is!

58:22.500 --> 58:24.041
-♪ I was wrong to ♪
-♪ Say you were wrong to ♪

58:24.125 --> 58:26.041
-♪ Say I was wrong about ♪
-♪ You being wrong ♪

58:26.125 --> 58:28.375
-♪ When you rang to say ♪
-♪ The ring was the wrong thing to bring ♪

58:28.458 --> 58:32.041
♪ If I meant what I said
When I said "rings bored me" ♪

58:32.125 --> 58:34.166
I don't know how
to get through to you anymore.

58:34.250 --> 58:36.958
You keep shutting me out,
you keep putting up these fences.

58:37.041 --> 58:40.583
-I'm not. I'm not shutting you out.
-You're a million miles away all the time.

58:40.666 --> 58:44.000
-Actually, I'm right here.
-Are you, Jonathan?

58:44.083 --> 58:46.375
Actually? Because I know you.

58:46.458 --> 58:48.041
♪ I'm not mad
That you got mad ♪

58:48.125 --> 58:53.625
♪ When I got mad
When you said I should go drop dead ♪

58:53.708 --> 58:55.375
♪ If I were you
And I'd done what I'd done ♪

58:55.458 --> 58:57.291
♪ I'd do what you did
When I gave you the ring ♪

58:57.375 --> 59:00.041
♪ Having said what I said ♪

59:00.708 --> 59:04.875
You're right. I've been distracted,
but I promise you, after the workshop--

59:04.958 --> 59:06.083
After the workshop.

59:06.666 --> 59:08.833
After the workshop!

59:08.916 --> 59:11.083
Everything is after the workshop.

59:11.166 --> 59:12.166
Yeah.

59:12.250 --> 59:15.125
What if the workshop happens
and nothing changes?

59:15.208 --> 59:17.333
No producer with a big check.

59:17.416 --> 59:19.500
You don't go straight to Broadway.

59:19.583 --> 59:25.000
You're still a waiter, you're still living
in this apartment, you're still broke.

59:25.083 --> 59:29.250
What then, Jonathan? What about me?

59:29.333 --> 59:31.666
♪ I feel bad that you feel bad
About me feeling bad ♪

59:31.750 --> 59:34.166
♪ About you feeling bad about what I said
About what you said ♪

59:34.250 --> 59:36.750
♪ About me not being
Able to share a feeling ♪

59:36.833 --> 59:39.375
♪ Feeling badly about you ♪

59:39.458 --> 59:41.083
I can't move to the Berkshires.

59:41.166 --> 59:42.458
[scoffs]

59:42.541 --> 59:44.500
I can't leave my career behind.

59:45.291 --> 59:46.958
You think I don't know that?

59:47.875 --> 59:48.750
What?

59:50.083 --> 59:54.083
What are you…? What is this?
What do you want?

59:54.833 --> 59:56.458
[dry chuckle]

59:56.541 --> 1:00:00.583
I guess I just…
I wanted you to tell me not to go.

1:00:03.541 --> 1:00:05.375
♪ If I thought that what you thought ♪

1:00:05.458 --> 1:00:07.041
♪ Was I hadn't thought
About sharing my thoughts ♪

1:00:07.125 --> 1:00:09.333
♪ Then my reaction to your reaction
To my reaction ♪

1:00:09.416 --> 1:00:13.166
-♪ Would have been more revealing ♪
-♪ When I reacted to you ♪

1:00:13.250 --> 1:00:15.666
Of course I don't want you to go.

1:00:16.791 --> 1:00:19.083
-Really?
-Obviously.

1:00:19.166 --> 1:00:21.541
'Cause this is the first time
you've ever said it.

1:00:42.500 --> 1:00:43.958
Oh, my God.

1:00:44.666 --> 1:00:46.583
♪ Now it's out in the open ♪

1:00:46.666 --> 1:00:50.250
You're thinking about how you can
turn this into a song. Aren't you?

1:00:51.416 --> 1:00:53.666
♪ Now it's off our chest ♪

1:00:55.208 --> 1:00:57.208
No. What?

1:00:58.166 --> 1:01:02.375
You know what, Jonathan? I'm done.

1:01:03.708 --> 1:01:06.375
Susan? Susan, wait.

1:01:06.458 --> 1:01:10.125
I hope that you have an amazing workshop.

1:01:10.208 --> 1:01:13.166
Susan, hold on. Susan?

1:01:13.250 --> 1:01:16.208
♪ Now it's 4:00 a.m.
And we have therapy tomorrow ♪

1:01:16.291 --> 1:01:18.375
♪ It's too late to screw ♪

1:01:18.458 --> 1:01:20.875
♪ So let's just get some rest ♪

1:01:22.750 --> 1:01:26.291
[cheering, applause]

1:01:28.750 --> 1:01:30.083
[horn beeps]

1:01:31.000 --> 1:01:33.541
[ticking starts]

1:01:42.958 --> 1:01:45.083
[horn honking in the distance]

1:01:45.666 --> 1:01:48.333
So, just waiting on one more person.

1:01:48.416 --> 1:01:50.250
-[tired sigh]
-Enjoy those waters.

1:01:50.333 --> 1:01:51.416
[laughing]

1:01:51.500 --> 1:01:52.666
-So…
-[door opens]

1:01:53.416 --> 1:01:54.250
I'm Jon.

1:01:54.333 --> 1:01:56.708
-Yes, Mr. Larson, you're Michael's friend.
-Yeah.

1:01:56.791 --> 1:01:58.500
-How are you?
-Good. You're late.

1:01:58.583 --> 1:01:59.916
-Oh.
-Okay.

1:02:00.000 --> 1:02:01.458
-Sorry about that.
-That's okay.

1:02:01.541 --> 1:02:04.041
-No, because of the subway.
-Yeah, I'm sure.

1:02:04.125 --> 1:02:05.666
Take a seat when you can.

1:02:05.750 --> 1:02:07.041
-Hi.
-Welcome.

1:02:07.125 --> 1:02:08.583
Oh. Thanks.

1:02:08.666 --> 1:02:10.541
You sure there's no way
to get into the bathroom?

1:02:10.625 --> 1:02:12.458
Oh, no, you're not allowed
to use the bathroom.

1:02:12.541 --> 1:02:15.208
Sorry, did she mention
when we were gonna get paid?

1:02:15.291 --> 1:02:18.791
Okay, um, so now that we're all here…

1:02:18.875 --> 1:02:21.083
-Hi.
-Hey.

1:02:21.166 --> 1:02:24.583
Why don't we begin
with a quick brainstorming session? Right?

1:02:24.666 --> 1:02:28.041
Just to get those creative juices flowing.
You know what I mean? It'll be fun.

1:02:30.125 --> 1:02:31.541
Two hours of this.

1:02:31.625 --> 1:02:35.083
-For one extra musician.
-[laughter]

1:02:35.166 --> 1:02:37.958
So why don't we start
by you just throwing out some ideas

1:02:38.041 --> 1:02:41.916
when you hear me say the word "America."

1:02:42.000 --> 1:02:44.041
-George Washington.
-Excellent.

1:02:44.125 --> 1:02:46.375
-Abraham Lincoln.
-Abraham Lincoln. Okay.

1:02:46.458 --> 1:02:49.166
Empire, racism, genocide, Vietnam.

1:02:49.250 --> 1:02:50.666
Grover Cleveland.

1:02:52.375 --> 1:02:54.375
-The Constitution?
-Yes.

1:02:54.458 --> 1:02:56.458
-Yeah.
-Magna Carta.

1:02:57.083 --> 1:02:58.166
-The Bill of Rights.
-Mm-hm.

1:02:58.250 --> 1:03:00.500
-The right thing to do.
-Ooh.

1:03:00.583 --> 1:03:04.375
-[older woman] The right stuff.
-Right stuff.

1:03:05.000 --> 1:03:06.666
An open road at sunset.

1:03:09.083 --> 1:03:10.541
Wind in your hair.

1:03:11.875 --> 1:03:15.291
Nothing in your way, except horizon.

1:03:19.500 --> 1:03:23.625
That is beautiful, Mr. Larson.

1:03:23.708 --> 1:03:27.208
Wow. Okay. That goes on the board.

1:03:27.833 --> 1:03:30.708
-The sun.
-Sunrise.

1:03:31.291 --> 1:03:32.916
The dawn of a new day.

1:03:33.000 --> 1:03:36.083
-Oh! Where did you come from?
-It all goes back.

1:03:36.166 --> 1:03:38.958
-You're amazing.
-That is incredible.

1:03:39.041 --> 1:03:41.041
A window looking out on a field.

1:03:41.125 --> 1:03:44.500
Oh, and I look out, and I see
the bunnies and little squirrelies--

1:03:44.583 --> 1:03:46.625
The beating heart of the nation.

1:03:47.125 --> 1:03:49.291
-Ooh!
-[director] Oh, my gosh.

1:03:49.375 --> 1:03:52.041
-Absolutely. That's absolutely what it is.
-Beautiful.

1:03:52.125 --> 1:03:55.208
-I've never even heard that before.
-You are gifted.

1:03:56.708 --> 1:03:58.500
I could get used to this.

1:03:58.583 --> 1:04:00.916
[Jon] I could get paid for this.

1:04:01.000 --> 1:04:04.666
I could get health care. A 401(k).

1:04:05.541 --> 1:04:10.125
A BMW. A luxury apartment…
on Central Park West.

1:04:10.208 --> 1:04:12.791
-No, no, no… East.
-[laughter]

1:04:12.875 --> 1:04:18.041
I could actually be rewarded
for my creativity,

1:04:18.125 --> 1:04:21.416
instead of rejected and ignored.

1:04:22.416 --> 1:04:24.416
This could be the rest of my life.

1:04:25.208 --> 1:04:29.166
Now that we have all those
fabulous ideas of yours in our heads,

1:04:29.250 --> 1:04:32.125
we are going to turn to the task at hand.

1:04:32.208 --> 1:04:36.916
We are here to develop a name
of a revolutionary consumer product

1:04:37.000 --> 1:04:39.208
that is just about to hit your shelves.

1:04:39.291 --> 1:04:40.500
Oh. Wow.

1:04:40.583 --> 1:04:41.791
This is where we're gonna need

1:04:41.875 --> 1:04:44.458
that incredible imagination
of yours, Mr. Larson.

1:04:44.541 --> 1:04:48.708
So the product we're looking at
is a tasteless, odorless chemical compound

1:04:48.791 --> 1:04:51.625
that will be used as
a fat substitute in cooking.

1:04:51.708 --> 1:04:52.583
Mm.

1:04:52.666 --> 1:04:57.083
And it's been successfully tested
on a number of mammals.

1:04:57.166 --> 1:04:58.958
Well, that's good. Mm.

1:04:59.041 --> 1:05:01.166
There are some side effects
associated with the product

1:05:01.250 --> 1:05:03.125
that I've been instructed
to tell you about.

1:05:03.208 --> 1:05:05.000
So it's skin scales.

1:05:05.750 --> 1:05:07.458
Um… full hair loss.

1:05:07.541 --> 1:05:10.125
-Hair, eyebrows, eyelashes…
-[ominous music plays]

1:05:10.208 --> 1:05:12.458
This could be the rest of my life.

1:05:12.541 --> 1:05:15.458
And finally, in a small number of users,

1:05:15.541 --> 1:05:18.166
there were reports
of toxic shock syndrome…

1:05:18.958 --> 1:05:22.375
resulting in a brief hospitalization.

1:05:22.958 --> 1:05:25.416
-[man] Eh, no big deal.
-There are no bad ideas.

1:05:26.125 --> 1:05:27.083
[ticking starts]

1:05:27.166 --> 1:05:29.333
-Free oil.
-Love it.

1:05:29.416 --> 1:05:31.291
-Oil free.
-Okay.

1:05:31.375 --> 1:05:35.208
-That's the same thing she just said.
-I switched the words around.

1:05:35.291 --> 1:05:37.541
[director] That's totally fine, Kim.
Thank you so much.

1:05:37.625 --> 1:05:39.458
-The American Dream.
-Okay, well…

1:05:39.541 --> 1:05:41.250
-[Kim] Dreams of freedom.
-Okay.

1:05:41.333 --> 1:05:43.666
-[man] Nutra-oil.
-That's not bad, Todd.

1:05:43.750 --> 1:05:45.750
[Todd] Waist oil. No.

1:05:45.833 --> 1:05:49.291
-[ticking intensifies]
-[dialogue fades]

1:05:49.375 --> 1:05:51.958
[discordant music builds]

1:05:52.541 --> 1:05:53.708
I got it.

1:05:54.541 --> 1:05:56.708
[laughs triumphantly]

1:05:56.791 --> 1:05:59.666
-I have it. I have the exact--
-Go, go!

1:05:59.750 --> 1:06:03.083
You wanna hear? I got the exact
right thing for this product.

1:06:04.583 --> 1:06:06.500
Chubstitute.

1:06:10.166 --> 1:06:11.875
[Michael] Chubstitute?

1:06:11.958 --> 1:06:14.375
-It's a joke.
-It's not funny.

1:06:15.000 --> 1:06:18.375
-Well, maybe not to you but--
-I recommended you, Jon.

1:06:19.208 --> 1:06:21.458
I put my name on the line for you.

1:06:22.250 --> 1:06:24.875
-Tell them I had a stroke.
-It isn't funny.

1:06:26.333 --> 1:06:27.916
This is my life.

1:06:28.000 --> 1:06:31.541
No, it's not your life, it's advertising.

1:06:31.625 --> 1:06:33.708
It's figuring out how to trick people

1:06:33.791 --> 1:06:36.833
into buying shit that they don't want.

1:06:36.916 --> 1:06:39.000
Actually, it's a lot more
complicated than that.

1:06:39.083 --> 1:06:41.833
I don't understand how
you can take any of this seriously.

1:06:41.916 --> 1:06:44.166
-Because they pay me to.
-Money isn't everything.

1:06:44.250 --> 1:06:46.833
-Well, it doesn't hurt.
-Are you sure about that?

1:06:48.041 --> 1:06:50.541
What are you doing with your life
that's so noble?

1:06:52.208 --> 1:06:55.375
-I'm making art.
-That's what the world needs. More art.

1:06:55.458 --> 1:06:59.416
Actually, yes. And at least
I'm not perpetuating a system that's--

1:06:59.500 --> 1:07:00.958
Spare the self-righteousness, Jon.

1:07:01.041 --> 1:07:02.708
You're writing musicals
in your living room,

1:07:02.791 --> 1:07:04.500
you're not saving the rainforest.

1:07:07.125 --> 1:07:08.416
[whispers] Wow.

1:07:09.416 --> 1:07:11.833
Gosh, I wish I could be more like you,

1:07:11.916 --> 1:07:14.916
and spend my life caring
about driving the right car

1:07:15.000 --> 1:07:17.333
and wearing the right suits
and living in a doorman building.

1:07:17.416 --> 1:07:20.375
Why shouldn't I want those things, Jon?
Not all of us have options you do.

1:07:20.458 --> 1:07:22.625
All the things that you take for granted.

1:07:22.708 --> 1:07:25.375
-What? Like what?
-Like a life with the person you love.

1:07:25.458 --> 1:07:30.416
Do you know what I would give for that?
You-- You turn your nose up at it.

1:07:30.500 --> 1:07:33.125
If that's what you want,
what's stopping you?

1:07:33.208 --> 1:07:36.833
What's stopping me? How about
Jesse Helms and the Moral Majority?

1:07:36.916 --> 1:07:39.083
How about the people
that run this country?

1:07:39.166 --> 1:07:41.541
I can't get married. I can't have kids.

1:07:41.625 --> 1:07:46.625
Half our friends are dying and the other
half are scared to death they are next.

1:07:46.708 --> 1:07:49.291
So, I'm sorry for getting a nice car, Jon.

1:07:49.375 --> 1:07:52.958
I'm sorry for moving into
an apartment with central heating.

1:07:53.041 --> 1:07:56.750
I'm sorry for enjoying my life
while I still have time.

1:07:56.833 --> 1:07:57.875
I gotta go.

1:07:57.958 --> 1:07:59.083
Hey.

1:08:00.291 --> 1:08:01.833
You wanna come take the subway?

1:08:01.916 --> 1:08:03.916
-[Michael] I'd rather walk.
-Michael.

1:08:04.000 --> 1:08:04.916
Michael.

1:08:08.708 --> 1:08:09.875
[phone ringing]

1:08:09.958 --> 1:08:11.958
-[footsteps approach]
-[door opens]

1:08:14.458 --> 1:08:15.458
Hello?

1:08:15.541 --> 1:08:18.416
[woman] Johnny, darling. It's Rosa.

1:08:18.500 --> 1:08:20.125
[gasps]

1:08:20.208 --> 1:08:22.333
-Hello?
-Rosa Stevens?

1:08:22.416 --> 1:08:25.833
-Are we excited for tomorrow?
-Tomorrow?

1:08:26.541 --> 1:08:28.500
The presentation.
You remembered the presentation?

1:08:28.583 --> 1:08:31.583
Remembered it?
I got every producer in town coming.

1:08:31.666 --> 1:08:32.833
-[sighs]
-[Rosa laughs]

1:08:32.916 --> 1:08:34.791
-[laughs]
-So it better be good.

1:08:34.875 --> 1:08:39.500
Yeah, it's, uh… it's gonna be amazing.

1:08:39.583 --> 1:08:42.208
Let's see if we can't get
a bidding war started

1:08:42.291 --> 1:08:44.916
on this musical of yours. What do you say?

1:08:45.791 --> 1:08:48.208
Yes, sure. [laughs nervously]

1:08:48.291 --> 1:08:50.166
Okay, doll.

1:08:50.250 --> 1:08:53.833
Charlie, get me Hal Prince on the line.

1:08:53.916 --> 1:08:55.250
Rosa? Um, I--

1:08:55.333 --> 1:08:56.833
[dial tone]

1:08:56.916 --> 1:08:58.958
[breathing deeply]

1:09:03.416 --> 1:09:05.750
[up-tempo rock music playing]

1:09:18.250 --> 1:09:19.125
[gagging]

1:09:20.458 --> 1:09:21.750
I'm so sorry.

1:09:31.125 --> 1:09:32.333
[door squeaks]

1:09:33.750 --> 1:09:35.208
Yeah. I know, I know, I know.

1:09:47.416 --> 1:09:49.000
[music stops]

1:09:49.083 --> 1:09:51.500
[kettle whistle dying]

1:09:54.666 --> 1:09:56.083
[whispers] Oh, no.

1:09:57.166 --> 1:09:59.791
Why wouldn't you have called me
to tell me my payment was late

1:09:59.875 --> 1:10:02.000
before you just cut off my power?

1:10:02.083 --> 1:10:04.291
How is--? How does that make sense?

1:10:04.375 --> 1:10:06.541
[man] Sir, as I explained before,
you received a notice--

1:10:06.625 --> 1:10:08.208
No, no, no, listen.

1:10:08.291 --> 1:10:10.500
You don't understand. I have a workshop.

1:10:10.583 --> 1:10:14.500
I have a public presentation
of my musical in 12 hours…

1:10:14.583 --> 1:10:17.166
Sir, if you are going to raise your voice…

1:10:17.250 --> 1:10:18.750
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

1:10:18.833 --> 1:10:22.208
Look, look, look.
I can pay you over the phone, right now.

1:10:22.291 --> 1:10:25.875
-I have my credit card right here…
-The billing office is closed.

1:10:25.958 --> 1:10:28.416
I would love to figure it out right now.

1:10:28.500 --> 1:10:30.666
The billing office is closed
for the night.

1:10:30.750 --> 1:10:32.041
[breathing heavily]

1:10:32.125 --> 1:10:35.416
-What am I gonna do?
-Sir, like I've said, call--

1:10:35.500 --> 1:10:38.291
[panting]

1:10:41.791 --> 1:10:43.375
[keypad beeping]

1:10:45.833 --> 1:10:48.291
[line ringing]

1:10:48.375 --> 1:10:52.125
-[woman] Hello?
-Hey, Beth. Hey.

1:10:52.208 --> 1:10:54.666
How are you? It's Jon.

1:10:54.750 --> 1:10:55.791
Hi, Jon.

1:10:55.875 --> 1:10:58.708
Hi, um… is Susan there?

1:10:58.791 --> 1:11:00.583
She doesn't wanna talk to you, Jon.

1:11:03.000 --> 1:11:03.833
Yeah.

1:11:04.750 --> 1:11:05.875
Um…

1:11:06.875 --> 1:11:08.291
Sure, sure. Uh…

1:11:08.375 --> 1:11:12.375
Well, can you… um…
can you give her a message for me?

1:11:12.458 --> 1:11:15.208
-What is it?
-Well, it's just, you know…

1:11:16.250 --> 1:11:20.333
I wanted to remind her that tomorrow
is my workshop and you know, I…

1:11:21.041 --> 1:11:24.000
I know I don't have any right to ask this.
It's just that…

1:11:25.916 --> 1:11:28.250
I would just really love her to be there.

1:11:28.791 --> 1:11:30.500
I'll tell her you called.

1:11:30.583 --> 1:11:31.916
[line clicks]

1:11:37.250 --> 1:11:38.833
[Jon] Here I am.

1:11:38.916 --> 1:11:40.250
[ticking starts]

1:11:41.125 --> 1:11:44.541
The musical to which
I have devoted my youth

1:11:44.625 --> 1:11:49.750
is about to be put on public display
for every producer in New York.

1:11:49.833 --> 1:11:51.625
[ticking continues]

1:11:51.708 --> 1:11:56.083
I haven't written a single note
or a single lyric

1:11:56.166 --> 1:11:59.625
of the most important song in the show.

1:12:01.375 --> 1:12:03.166
I have no electricity.

1:12:04.125 --> 1:12:08.375
My best friend is furious with me.
My girlfriend isn't speaking to me.

1:12:09.375 --> 1:12:13.000
And there is only
one thing I can think of to do:

1:12:15.625 --> 1:12:16.625
Swim.

1:12:16.708 --> 1:12:19.000
[propulsive rock music playing]

1:12:24.916 --> 1:12:29.333
♪ I hate this locker room
Why won't Susan answer my calls? ♪

1:12:29.416 --> 1:12:32.833
♪ Sweat, wet, echo
Smell, hell, rap ♪

1:12:32.916 --> 1:12:35.791
♪ Pump up the volume
Hot, wet, hot sweat ♪

1:12:35.875 --> 1:12:37.333
♪ How's the water? ♪

1:12:37.416 --> 1:12:39.583
♪ Stretch, stretch
Spit in the mask ♪

1:12:39.666 --> 1:12:41.208
♪ Cloudy vision
Test the water ♪

1:12:41.291 --> 1:12:44.416
♪ Contemplate the dive
The shock to the skin ♪

1:12:44.500 --> 1:12:48.791
♪ Anticipate the pain, the pain, the pain
The pain, the pain now ♪

1:12:48.875 --> 1:12:51.916
♪ One, two, three,
Oh, bite the air, seven ♪

1:12:52.000 --> 1:12:54.000
♪ There's that girl
One, two, three ♪

1:12:54.083 --> 1:12:56.541
♪ Oh, bite the air
Smooth, soft skin ♪

1:12:56.625 --> 1:12:59.166
♪ Two, three
Oh, bite the-- Thirteen ♪

1:12:59.250 --> 1:13:02.375
♪ Long legs, brown skin and wet hair ♪

1:13:02.458 --> 1:13:05.833
♪ Whoa, and wet hair ♪

1:13:05.916 --> 1:13:08.875
♪ Has Rosa even listened to my tape? ♪

1:13:08.958 --> 1:13:12.541
♪ Kick, stretch, windmill arms
See the hand, point the feet ♪

1:13:12.625 --> 1:13:16.375
♪ Wet hair
Relax, this guy's too slow ♪

1:13:16.458 --> 1:13:18.500
♪ Fifteen
Can I make it to 40? ♪

1:13:18.583 --> 1:13:20.458
♪ Too slow
Touch his heel, move! ♪

1:13:20.541 --> 1:13:22.583
♪ Answer my calls!
Red thin stripe ♪

1:13:22.666 --> 1:13:26.333
♪ Fifty feet, sixty feet
She looks like Susan ♪

1:13:26.416 --> 1:13:28.041
♪ Susan's beautiful ♪

1:13:28.666 --> 1:13:31.750
♪ Out, don't think, out, out
Let it out ♪

1:13:31.833 --> 1:13:35.041
♪ Keep the shoulder down, down ♪

1:13:35.125 --> 1:13:37.208
♪ Easy, not too hard ♪

1:13:37.291 --> 1:13:41.958
♪ Find the movement's origin ♪

1:13:42.041 --> 1:13:45.041
♪ Hands, no
Shoulder, no ♪

1:13:45.125 --> 1:13:46.791
♪ Elbows, no ♪

1:13:46.875 --> 1:13:49.875
♪ Lower, from the back
Yes, lower ♪

1:13:49.958 --> 1:13:52.333
♪ Thirty-nine, 40 ♪

1:13:52.416 --> 1:13:54.458
♪ Center, center ♪

1:13:54.541 --> 1:13:57.375
[atmospheric piano interlude begins]

1:14:20.708 --> 1:14:23.541
♪ Forward motion ♪

1:14:23.625 --> 1:14:26.500
♪ Through the water ♪

1:14:26.583 --> 1:14:28.375
♪ Come to your senses ♪

1:14:28.458 --> 1:14:31.125
-♪ Escape ♪
-♪ Come to your senses ♪

1:14:31.208 --> 1:14:33.875
♪ Come to your senses ♪

1:14:33.958 --> 1:14:37.208
♪ I am soaring ♪

1:14:37.291 --> 1:14:40.458
-♪ I'm the water ♪
-♪ You're on the air ♪

1:14:40.541 --> 1:14:43.583
-♪ You as the knight ♪
-♪ I'm underground ♪

1:14:43.666 --> 1:14:46.958
♪ Me as the queen ♪

1:14:53.708 --> 1:14:55.791
[rock music resumes]

1:15:22.750 --> 1:15:24.333
[music stops]

1:15:24.416 --> 1:15:26.875
[clock ticking]

1:15:26.958 --> 1:15:28.625
[Jon] The show is about to begin.

1:15:29.666 --> 1:15:32.333
The room is completely empty.

1:15:34.541 --> 1:15:39.041
The show is about to begin,
and I am looking

1:15:39.125 --> 1:15:43.833
at 60 empty folding chairs.

1:15:43.916 --> 1:15:45.000
[door opens]

1:15:45.083 --> 1:15:47.166
[ticking continues]

1:15:47.791 --> 1:15:48.708
[whispers] Hi.

1:15:49.708 --> 1:15:51.291
Hey, boy genius.

1:15:52.000 --> 1:15:53.458
[ticking continues]

1:15:53.541 --> 1:15:55.500
I'm turning 30 on Sunday, you know.

1:15:56.208 --> 1:15:57.791
Oh, well, happy birthday.

1:15:58.500 --> 1:15:59.375
Thank you.

1:16:00.625 --> 1:16:03.458
-Thirty's still young, you know.
-No one's here.

1:16:04.625 --> 1:16:06.583
Oh. It's not even 9:00.

1:16:08.791 --> 1:16:11.166
The presentation doesn't start till 10:00.

1:16:11.250 --> 1:16:13.750
-[ticking stops]
-[sighs with relief]

1:16:16.666 --> 1:16:17.791
[Jon] Oh…

1:16:18.375 --> 1:16:19.750
That's good.

1:16:20.333 --> 1:16:22.208
-Cool. [laughs]
-[laughing]

1:16:22.291 --> 1:16:24.416
Okay. [panting]

1:16:25.208 --> 1:16:27.416
-Can you sight read?
-Yeah.

1:16:30.625 --> 1:16:32.166
[exhales]

1:16:33.000 --> 1:16:37.500
[Jon] Slowly, miraculously,
people start to show up.

1:16:37.583 --> 1:16:40.291
-Johnny.
-[Jon] Be right back.

1:16:40.375 --> 1:16:43.708
This is phenomenal.
Look at the space, it's just phenomenal.

1:16:43.791 --> 1:16:47.333
-It's a rehearsal studio, Dad.
-It's a Broadway rehearsal studio.

1:16:47.416 --> 1:16:50.416
-This is the real thing.
-We're so excited for you, dear.

1:16:50.500 --> 1:16:52.875
-Thank you.
-Are they paying you?

1:16:54.375 --> 1:16:56.166
-No.
-[sighs]

1:16:56.250 --> 1:16:58.458
-Next time.
-Sure.

1:16:58.541 --> 1:17:01.208
-[father] Oh, look, for us.
-No, that's not…

1:17:01.291 --> 1:17:04.333
-That's for someone else, actually.
-Mm. Do you like that?

1:17:04.416 --> 1:17:08.416
You can literally sit in any other seat.

1:17:09.291 --> 1:17:11.291
-Okay. Break a leg.
-Shall we sit there?

1:17:11.375 --> 1:17:13.791
-I love you. Thank you.
-I love you.

1:17:20.000 --> 1:17:21.958
His hair is ridiculous.

1:17:22.041 --> 1:17:24.625
[low, indistinct chatter]

1:17:29.083 --> 1:17:30.083
Good turnout.

1:17:32.041 --> 1:17:33.875
Yeah, mostly friends.

1:17:34.916 --> 1:17:36.708
Mm, what a nightmare.

1:17:38.291 --> 1:17:40.291
[both chuckle lightly]

1:17:41.833 --> 1:17:45.416
Thank you… for being here.

1:17:46.583 --> 1:17:49.625
Wild horses, Jon. You know that.

1:17:53.125 --> 1:17:56.375
-Oh! Okay. Break legs.
-Yeah.

1:17:59.416 --> 1:18:01.791
Oh. Thank you. Thank you.

1:18:02.500 --> 1:18:04.875
Ira, you son of a gun.

1:18:04.958 --> 1:18:08.166
-Jonathan, how are you?
-Rosa.

1:18:09.958 --> 1:18:12.541
-Jon Larson.
-Oh, there he is.

1:18:12.625 --> 1:18:16.750
Just the man I'm looking for.
You nervous? Don't be nervous.

1:18:16.833 --> 1:18:19.833
-Yeah. A little nervous. Sure.
-Of course you're nervous.

1:18:19.916 --> 1:18:24.791
The first presentation of your musical is
like having a colonoscopy in Times Square.

1:18:24.875 --> 1:18:27.416
Only with a colonoscopy,
the worst thing that could happen

1:18:27.500 --> 1:18:29.333
is you find out you have cancer.

1:18:29.416 --> 1:18:32.958
With a musical,
you find out you're already dead.

1:18:35.958 --> 1:18:38.416
Have a good show.
Can't wait to see what you did.

1:18:44.791 --> 1:18:47.541
We can't keep waiting. It's quarter past.

1:18:47.625 --> 1:18:49.208
I know. I know. I know.

1:18:49.833 --> 1:18:51.333
-Break a leg.
-Okay.

1:18:52.333 --> 1:18:54.041
Come here. Thank you.

1:18:54.833 --> 1:18:56.166
[sighs]

1:19:10.625 --> 1:19:13.208
Hello. Hi, welcome.

1:19:14.416 --> 1:19:16.041
I'm Jonathan Larson.

1:19:16.125 --> 1:19:18.000
[applause, cheering]

1:19:18.083 --> 1:19:20.583
Whoa… Hey, well…

1:19:20.666 --> 1:19:24.625
You don't have to do that.
Thank you so much, that was very kind. Uh…

1:19:24.708 --> 1:19:27.416
Thank you for being here,
um, this morning.

1:19:27.500 --> 1:19:28.833
-This is, um…
-[door shuts]

1:19:34.833 --> 1:19:37.666
-[whispering] That's Stephen Sondheim.
-Right. Like I was saying…

1:19:37.750 --> 1:19:41.000
Thank you all for being here.
This is my musical, Superbia,

1:19:41.083 --> 1:19:45.166
and I've been working on it for…
a little while now.

1:19:45.250 --> 1:19:46.666
[chuckles lightly]

1:19:46.750 --> 1:19:49.458
And I just really hope you all like it.

1:19:51.250 --> 1:19:52.291
Thank you.

1:19:52.375 --> 1:19:54.041
[applause]

1:19:57.916 --> 1:20:00.041
[up-tempo music begins]

1:20:01.166 --> 1:20:05.583
And the next hour and a half are a blur.

1:20:06.666 --> 1:20:12.125
♪ Everyone who ever has
Or ever will be anyone will be there ♪

1:20:12.833 --> 1:20:19.375
♪ Never in the history of entertainment
Will there be an affair quite like it ♪

1:20:19.458 --> 1:20:22.041
♪ The event of the century ♪

1:20:22.125 --> 1:20:24.333
♪ The quintessential social adventure ♪

1:20:24.416 --> 1:20:28.458
♪ We cannot afford to miss
This night of bliss ♪

1:20:28.541 --> 1:20:31.833
♪ Everyone who's anyone knows
Everyone who's anyone knows ♪

1:20:31.916 --> 1:20:34.958
♪ Everyone who's anyone
Everyone who's anyone knows ♪

1:20:35.041 --> 1:20:42.041
♪ Everyone will be there ♪

1:20:43.375 --> 1:20:44.791
And then…

1:20:46.000 --> 1:20:49.541
Karessa steps forward to sing my new song.

1:20:50.458 --> 1:20:52.333
Not even 12 hours old.

1:20:52.916 --> 1:20:54.375
I close my eyes.

1:20:55.666 --> 1:20:57.291
I brace myself.

1:20:58.416 --> 1:21:00.333
I don't dare take a breath.

1:21:01.125 --> 1:21:04.125
[lilting melody plays]

1:21:04.708 --> 1:21:06.416
But when I open my eyes…

1:21:07.833 --> 1:21:09.708
I don't see Karessa there.

1:21:22.500 --> 1:21:25.375
♪ You're on the air ♪

1:21:27.083 --> 1:21:30.125
♪ I'm underground ♪

1:21:32.250 --> 1:21:37.291
♪ Signal's fading ♪

1:21:37.375 --> 1:21:41.166
♪ Can't be found ♪

1:21:42.333 --> 1:21:46.041
♪ I finally open up ♪

1:21:47.541 --> 1:21:50.833
♪ For you, I would do anything ♪

1:21:52.791 --> 1:21:57.041
♪ But you've turned off the volume ♪

1:21:57.708 --> 1:22:04.708
♪ Just when I've begun to sing ♪

1:22:06.125 --> 1:22:07.833
♪ Come to your senses ♪

1:22:07.916 --> 1:22:11.375
♪ Defenses are not the way to go ♪

1:22:11.458 --> 1:22:15.708
♪ And you know, or at least you knew ♪

1:22:15.791 --> 1:22:19.791
♪ Can't you recall when this all began ♪

1:22:19.875 --> 1:22:22.666
♪ It was only you and me ♪

1:22:22.750 --> 1:22:29.750
♪ It was only me and you ♪

1:22:31.708 --> 1:22:35.375
♪ I have to laugh ♪

1:22:36.000 --> 1:22:39.791
♪ We sure put on a show ♪

1:22:41.333 --> 1:22:46.000
♪ Love is passé in this day and age ♪

1:22:46.083 --> 1:22:50.083
♪ How can we expect it to grow? ♪

1:22:51.250 --> 1:22:55.125
♪ You as the knight ♪

1:22:56.291 --> 1:22:59.958
♪ Me as the queen ♪

1:23:01.416 --> 1:23:06.083
♪ All I've got tonight ♪

1:23:06.166 --> 1:23:13.166
♪ Is static on a screen ♪

1:23:14.125 --> 1:23:17.541
♪ Come to your senses
Suspense is fine ♪

1:23:17.625 --> 1:23:20.083
♪ If you're just an empty image ♪

1:23:20.166 --> 1:23:23.458
♪ Emanating out of a screen ♪

1:23:23.541 --> 1:23:27.458
♪ Baby, be real
You can feel again ♪

1:23:27.541 --> 1:23:30.541
♪ You don't need a music box melody ♪

1:23:30.625 --> 1:23:34.333
♪ To know what I mean ♪

1:23:34.416 --> 1:23:38.750
♪ Deep in my eyes
What do you see? ♪

1:23:39.500 --> 1:23:44.625
♪ Deep in my sighs
Listen to me ♪

1:23:44.708 --> 1:23:49.208
♪ Let the music commence from inside ♪

1:23:49.291 --> 1:23:53.541
♪ Not only one sense, but use all five ♪

1:23:53.625 --> 1:23:56.375
♪ Come to your senses ♪

1:23:56.458 --> 1:23:58.583
♪ Come to your senses ♪

1:23:58.666 --> 1:24:03.708
-♪ Come to your senses, yeah ♪
-♪ Come to your senses ♪

1:24:03.791 --> 1:24:06.208
♪ Come to your senses ♪

1:24:06.291 --> 1:24:13.250
♪ Baby, come back ♪

1:24:14.041 --> 1:24:21.041
♪ Alive ♪

1:24:26.833 --> 1:24:29.375
[clapping, cheering]

1:24:37.333 --> 1:24:38.750
Whoo!

1:24:42.958 --> 1:24:44.375
[breathing shakily]

1:24:48.041 --> 1:24:49.708
[phone rings]

1:24:50.583 --> 1:24:52.875
-Hello?
-Hi, honey, it's Rosa.

1:24:52.958 --> 1:24:54.916
Hi, Rosa. Thank you so much for calling.

1:24:55.000 --> 1:24:57.791
Well, you already left six messages.

1:24:57.875 --> 1:25:02.083
[chuckles] Yeah. Um…
So have you heard anything yet?

1:25:02.166 --> 1:25:07.125
Honey, I have heard nothing
but raves all day long.

1:25:07.208 --> 1:25:09.708
I'm getting call after call after call.

1:25:10.875 --> 1:25:12.083
Wow. [chuckles]

1:25:12.166 --> 1:25:15.375
Okay. Yes! That's great news.

1:25:15.458 --> 1:25:19.041
Everyone is telling me the same thing.
"That Jonathan Larson!"

1:25:19.125 --> 1:25:22.041
"I can't wait to see what he does next."

1:25:23.625 --> 1:25:26.666
What do you mean, what I do next?
What about Superbia?

1:25:28.000 --> 1:25:31.083
I always told you, it was a tough sell.

1:25:31.166 --> 1:25:33.208
It's too arty for Broadway.

1:25:33.291 --> 1:25:36.500
Tourists aren't gonna shell out 50 dollars

1:25:36.583 --> 1:25:39.083
to see a show about spaceships and robots.

1:25:39.166 --> 1:25:42.833
Um… That's not what it's about. Um…

1:25:42.916 --> 1:25:45.541
Well, of course, I know that, Jonathan.

1:25:45.625 --> 1:25:49.583
But you know these producers, they care
about one thing and one thing only.

1:25:49.666 --> 1:25:54.541
Okay. Uh… So what about Off-Broadway?

1:25:54.625 --> 1:25:57.083
It's too expensive for Off.

1:25:57.750 --> 1:26:00.958
You got a cast of thousands,
with the special effects…

1:26:01.041 --> 1:26:03.416
Uh… Charlie, tell him I'll be on in a sec.

1:26:03.500 --> 1:26:05.416
-Listen, sweetie, I gotta run.
-I'm sorry, Rosa…

1:26:05.500 --> 1:26:08.708
Congratulations
on a terrific presentation.

1:26:08.791 --> 1:26:10.208
Rosa, Rosa, hold on.

1:26:10.791 --> 1:26:12.750
So, okay…

1:26:13.541 --> 1:26:16.041
So what am I supposed to do now?

1:26:19.125 --> 1:26:21.041
You start writing the next one.

1:26:21.833 --> 1:26:25.208
And after you finish that one,
you start on the next.

1:26:25.291 --> 1:26:31.000
And on and on, and that's
what it is to be a writer, honey.

1:26:31.791 --> 1:26:34.541
You just keep throwing them
against the wall

1:26:34.625 --> 1:26:39.541
and hoping against hope
that eventually, something sticks.

1:26:43.750 --> 1:26:45.041
[phone beeps]

1:26:46.875 --> 1:26:47.708
Listen.

1:26:47.791 --> 1:26:52.458
Little advice from someone who's
been in this business a long, long time?

1:26:54.500 --> 1:27:00.208
On the next one, maybe
try writing about what you know.

1:27:04.208 --> 1:27:05.583
Okay, kiddo?

1:27:07.250 --> 1:27:08.083
Yeah.

1:27:08.833 --> 1:27:11.416
Start sharpening those pencils.

1:27:12.208 --> 1:27:13.666
Yeah, yeah.

1:27:14.708 --> 1:27:15.875
[phone disconnects]

1:27:20.375 --> 1:27:22.375
[busy tone]

1:27:23.625 --> 1:27:27.791
I think let's give it a minute
and see what happens next week.

1:27:27.875 --> 1:27:29.291
Hey, I need a job.

1:27:29.375 --> 1:27:32.750
-Can you hold on a second?
-I'll apologize to the focus group lady.

1:27:32.833 --> 1:27:35.916
I will never say anything bad
about marketing research ever again,

1:27:36.000 --> 1:27:37.333
I swear to God.

1:27:37.416 --> 1:27:39.208
I'm gonna call you right back.

1:27:39.291 --> 1:27:41.250
I wanna do what you do.
I wanna have what you have.

1:27:41.333 --> 1:27:45.666
I want the BMW, I want the doorman,
I want it, I want all of it. Okay?

1:27:45.750 --> 1:27:47.875
-What's going on?
-Oh, it's good. It's good.

1:27:47.958 --> 1:27:49.916
I just spent
the last eight years killing myself

1:27:50.000 --> 1:27:52.041
on a musical that's never gonna happen.

1:27:52.125 --> 1:27:55.333
I find that very hard to believe.
It was incredible this morning.

1:27:55.416 --> 1:27:57.875
Well…But not incredible enough.

1:27:58.375 --> 1:27:59.708
I can't do it again, Mike.

1:27:59.791 --> 1:28:03.333
I can't stomach five more years
of waiting tables,

1:28:03.416 --> 1:28:06.708
five more years of writing things
that no one will ever see

1:28:06.791 --> 1:28:08.875
while Broadway just churns out
mega-musicals

1:28:08.958 --> 1:28:12.125
without a hint of even
the slightest thing original

1:28:12.208 --> 1:28:16.416
or, God forbid, something
to actually say about the world!

1:28:17.708 --> 1:28:18.916
Are you done?

1:28:19.958 --> 1:28:22.666
-No, actually--
-The presentation, Jon, it was amazing.

1:28:23.958 --> 1:28:26.625
It would be a tragedy
to give up what you have.

1:28:27.666 --> 1:28:30.500
-You did it.
-Please! [laughs]

1:28:30.583 --> 1:28:32.583
I was a mediocre actor.

1:28:32.666 --> 1:28:35.916
Do you know how many mediocre actors
there are in New York City?

1:28:36.000 --> 1:28:38.958
Do you know how many
Jonathan Larsons there are?

1:28:39.958 --> 1:28:40.916
One.

1:28:43.166 --> 1:28:45.916
I can't keep wasting my time, Mike.

1:28:46.000 --> 1:28:48.416
-I turn 30 in two days.
-And?

1:28:49.416 --> 1:28:53.750
And Stephen Sondheim was 27
when he had his first show on Broadway.

1:28:53.833 --> 1:28:56.791
Well, guess what? You're not
Stephen Sondheim. Wait a little longer--

1:28:56.875 --> 1:28:59.291
I'm not waiting anymore.
I can't keep waiting. This is my life.

1:28:59.375 --> 1:29:02.083
-I understand.
-No, you don't. I'm running out of time.

1:29:02.875 --> 1:29:06.875
-You are not running out of time.
-You don't know anything about it.

1:29:06.958 --> 1:29:08.541
I'm HIV-positive.

1:29:16.833 --> 1:29:17.833
What?

1:29:23.750 --> 1:29:26.250
-How long have you known?
-A few days.

1:29:31.166 --> 1:29:32.250
Who knows?

1:29:33.666 --> 1:29:35.416
I might get lucky. People do.

1:29:37.375 --> 1:29:40.000
Live a year, longer even.

1:29:42.833 --> 1:29:46.625
Anyway, I think I might know
a thing or two about running out of time.

1:29:47.708 --> 1:29:49.208
Why didn't you tell me sooner?

1:29:55.750 --> 1:29:56.750
You tried.

1:30:01.958 --> 1:30:04.625
-[phone rings]
-[woman] Jill Kramer returning, line two.

1:30:06.750 --> 1:30:08.458
I have to take that.

1:30:08.541 --> 1:30:11.583
-Mike--
-I can't talk about this now, please.

1:30:15.541 --> 1:30:18.500
Jill. Hey, it's Michael.

1:30:18.583 --> 1:30:21.166
Yeah, I just want to see how
the Downy account was going.

1:30:21.250 --> 1:30:23.875
-[ticking starts]
-Mm-hm.

1:30:23.958 --> 1:30:27.291
-[elevator dings]
-[indistinct chatter]

1:30:32.250 --> 1:30:34.291
[Jon] I think of the day I met Michael.

1:30:34.375 --> 1:30:36.166
[ticking continues]

1:30:36.250 --> 1:30:40.375
[Jon] It was the first day
at sleep-away camp, 22 years ago.

1:30:41.583 --> 1:30:42.958
We were eight.

1:30:44.125 --> 1:30:47.666
I think of high school,
all the shows we did together.

1:30:49.000 --> 1:30:50.208
[elevator dings]

1:30:55.958 --> 1:31:02.083
♪ Is this real life? ♪

1:31:02.833 --> 1:31:05.916
I think of the summer that
our parents decided to stay

1:31:06.000 --> 1:31:09.916
in the same town in Cape Cod,
a mile away from each other.

1:31:10.000 --> 1:31:12.541
And we'd meet on the beach
every night and, um…

1:31:13.791 --> 1:31:19.500
we'd just sit there talking
till three in the morning about our plans.

1:31:21.458 --> 1:31:25.333
[crying] About how one day we were
gonna move to the city together and…

1:31:25.416 --> 1:31:26.250
[sniffles]

1:31:26.333 --> 1:31:30.000
…find a cheap apartment and be discovered,

1:31:30.750 --> 1:31:32.458
and change the world.

1:31:33.375 --> 1:31:36.125
[woman on recording]
Hey, you've reached Susan, Beth--

1:31:36.208 --> 1:31:37.250
[phone clatters]

1:31:39.333 --> 1:31:42.625
[Jon] I think of the first summer
back from college.

1:31:42.708 --> 1:31:46.875
We smoked a bowl on Kennedy breakwater
and Michael told me he was gay.

1:31:47.750 --> 1:31:53.708
♪ Is this real life? ♪

1:31:55.041 --> 1:31:58.500
♪ Is this real life? ♪

1:31:58.583 --> 1:32:01.625
[Jon] I think of our friends, so many.

1:32:02.541 --> 1:32:04.791
-I think of their funerals.
-[sobbing]

1:32:04.875 --> 1:32:07.000
[Jon] I think of their parents
not even 50,

1:32:07.083 --> 1:32:09.833
saying the Kaddish over their children.

1:32:09.916 --> 1:32:15.291
♪ Is this real life? ♪

1:32:16.625 --> 1:32:19.250
[Jon] I think of them
and I think of Michael.

1:32:19.333 --> 1:32:23.083
And before I understand
what's happening, I start running.

1:32:23.166 --> 1:32:29.458
♪ Is this real life? ♪

1:32:30.125 --> 1:32:33.208
Past the pond, past the carousel.

1:32:33.291 --> 1:32:36.041
[ticking intensifies]

1:32:37.208 --> 1:32:40.041
♪ Is this real life? ♪

1:32:40.125 --> 1:32:43.875
[Jon] The ticking is so loud now,
I can't hear anything.

1:32:43.958 --> 1:32:47.000
♪ Is this real?
Is this real? ♪

1:32:47.083 --> 1:32:48.625
♪ Is this real? ♪

1:32:48.708 --> 1:32:51.875
My heartbeat is pounding in my throat.

1:32:51.958 --> 1:32:55.291
The wind is shrieking through the trees.

1:32:55.375 --> 1:32:57.166
The sky is darkening.

1:32:57.250 --> 1:33:01.083
I want it to stop.
[crying] I want it all to stop!

1:33:02.208 --> 1:33:04.875
[ticking continues]

1:33:05.791 --> 1:33:08.125
[birds calling]

1:33:09.291 --> 1:33:11.791
[ticking continues]

1:33:37.291 --> 1:33:40.000
[ticking accelerates]

1:34:03.541 --> 1:34:05.041
[ticking stops]

1:34:06.000 --> 1:34:07.500
[exhales deeply]

1:34:10.000 --> 1:34:13.250
[gentle melody plays]

1:34:24.958 --> 1:34:27.958
♪ When I was nine ♪

1:34:28.041 --> 1:34:31.666
♪ Michael and I ♪

1:34:31.750 --> 1:34:36.458
♪ Entered a talent show down at the Y ♪

1:34:38.333 --> 1:34:43.583
♪ Nine a.m.
Went to rehearse by some stairs ♪

1:34:44.666 --> 1:34:46.958
[sobbing] ♪ Mike couldn't sing ♪

1:34:47.041 --> 1:34:49.833
♪ I said, "No one cares" ♪

1:34:50.541 --> 1:34:55.791
♪ We sang "Yellow Bird" ♪

1:34:56.666 --> 1:35:00.666
♪ And "Let's Go Fly a Kite" ♪

1:35:01.666 --> 1:35:05.041
♪ Over and over and over ♪

1:35:05.125 --> 1:35:09.750
♪ Till we got it right ♪

1:35:10.375 --> 1:35:13.291
♪ When we emerged ♪

1:35:14.166 --> 1:35:16.375
♪ From the YMCA ♪

1:35:17.166 --> 1:35:18.791
♪ Three o'clock sun ♪

1:35:18.875 --> 1:35:24.666
♪ Had made the grass hay ♪

1:35:26.458 --> 1:35:33.291
♪ I thought
Hey, what a way to spend the day ♪

1:35:34.541 --> 1:35:40.041
♪ Hey, what a way to spend the day ♪

1:35:41.416 --> 1:35:44.291
♪ I make a vow ♪

1:35:45.000 --> 1:35:47.958
♪ Right here and now ♪

1:35:48.625 --> 1:35:51.166
♪ I'm gonna spend ♪

1:35:52.000 --> 1:35:53.833
♪ My time this way ♪

1:35:55.291 --> 1:35:57.458
♪ When I was sixteen ♪

1:35:58.500 --> 1:36:01.416
♪ Michael and I ♪

1:36:01.500 --> 1:36:04.416
♪ Got parts in West Side ♪

1:36:04.500 --> 1:36:07.541
♪ At White Plains High ♪

1:36:07.625 --> 1:36:12.791
♪ Three o'clock
Went to rehearse in the gym ♪

1:36:13.666 --> 1:36:17.458
[laughing] ♪ Mike played Doc
Who did not sing ♪

1:36:17.541 --> 1:36:18.958
♪ Fine with him ♪

1:36:19.041 --> 1:36:24.083
♪ We sang
"Got a rocket in your pocket" ♪

1:36:24.166 --> 1:36:28.458
♪ And "The Jets are gonna
Have their day tonight" ♪

1:36:28.541 --> 1:36:31.458
♪ Over and over and over ♪

1:36:31.541 --> 1:36:36.500
♪ Till we got it right ♪

1:36:37.000 --> 1:36:39.875
♪ When we emerged ♪

1:36:40.958 --> 1:36:43.375
♪ Wiped out by that play ♪

1:36:44.250 --> 1:36:47.250
♪ Nine o'clock stars ♪

1:36:47.333 --> 1:36:50.916
♪ And moon lit the way ♪

1:36:53.625 --> 1:36:55.416
♪ I thought, hey ♪

1:36:56.208 --> 1:36:59.958
♪ What a way to spend the day ♪

1:37:01.625 --> 1:37:07.125
♪ Hey, what a way to spend the day ♪

1:37:07.875 --> 1:37:11.541
♪ I made a vow ♪

1:37:11.625 --> 1:37:14.625
♪ I wonder now ♪

1:37:14.708 --> 1:37:20.000
♪ Am I cut out
To spend my time this way? ♪

1:37:21.291 --> 1:37:23.833
♪ I'm twenty-nine ♪

1:37:24.708 --> 1:37:27.041
♪ Michael and I ♪

1:37:28.000 --> 1:37:33.333
♪ Live on the West Side of SoHo, NY ♪

1:37:34.375 --> 1:37:39.708
♪ Nine o'clock, I write a lyric or two ♪

1:37:40.500 --> 1:37:46.625
♪ Mike sings his song now on Mad Avenue ♪

1:37:46.708 --> 1:37:50.625
♪ I sing, "Come to your senses" ♪

1:37:50.708 --> 1:37:57.208
♪ "Defenses are not the way to go" ♪

1:37:58.541 --> 1:38:01.833
♪ Over and over and over ♪

1:38:01.916 --> 1:38:06.250
♪ And over and over
And over and over ♪

1:38:06.333 --> 1:38:11.083
♪ Till I get it right ♪

1:38:11.166 --> 1:38:16.375
♪ When I emerge from B Minor or A ♪

1:38:18.375 --> 1:38:21.916
♪ Five o'clock, diner calls ♪

1:38:23.000 --> 1:38:28.375
♪ I'm on my way ♪

1:38:30.916 --> 1:38:33.125
♪ I think, hey ♪

1:38:33.208 --> 1:38:37.458
♪ What a way to spend a day ♪

1:38:38.916 --> 1:38:44.416
♪ Hey, what a way to spend a day ♪

1:38:45.541 --> 1:38:48.291
♪ I make a vow ♪

1:38:49.208 --> 1:38:55.875
♪ Right here and now ♪

1:38:57.291 --> 1:39:00.125
♪ I'm gonna spend ♪

1:39:01.375 --> 1:39:04.208
♪ My time this way ♪

1:39:06.583 --> 1:39:09.416
♪ I'm gonna spend ♪

1:39:10.958 --> 1:39:17.958
♪ My time this way ♪

1:39:23.291 --> 1:39:24.875
[sighs shakily]

1:39:29.791 --> 1:39:31.000
[doorbell rings]

1:39:33.458 --> 1:39:38.125
Hey. Whatever happens next,
I'm here. I promise.

1:39:39.958 --> 1:39:43.458
There's, um… there's a support group,
it's called Friends In Deed.

1:39:43.541 --> 1:39:45.875
I just called them.
They have a meeting tomorrow morning.

1:39:45.958 --> 1:39:48.833
-You look like shit.
-[laughs]

1:39:48.916 --> 1:39:50.041
I'm so cold.

1:39:50.125 --> 1:39:51.541
[both chuckle]

1:39:51.625 --> 1:39:52.833
Come on.

1:39:54.916 --> 1:39:56.375
Oh, Mike.

1:39:57.916 --> 1:40:00.125
-[both crying]
-I'm sorry.

1:40:07.208 --> 1:40:08.541
Sunday.

1:40:10.666 --> 1:40:12.958
My 30th birthday.

1:40:18.333 --> 1:40:21.000
[phone rings]

1:40:25.458 --> 1:40:27.958
[phone continues to ring]

1:40:29.000 --> 1:40:31.833
-[Jon on machine] ♪ Speak ♪
-[beeps]

1:40:31.916 --> 1:40:33.500
Jon? Steve Sondheim here.

1:40:33.583 --> 1:40:36.291
Rosa gave me this number,
I hope it's okay to call you.

1:40:36.375 --> 1:40:39.041
I didn't get a chance to speak with you
after the reading,

1:40:39.125 --> 1:40:42.000
but I just wanted to say
it was really good.

1:40:42.083 --> 1:40:43.625
Congratulations.

1:40:43.708 --> 1:40:46.708
I'd love to get together and talk to
you about it, if you have any interest.

1:40:46.791 --> 1:40:48.208
-No pressure.
-[chuckles]

1:40:48.291 --> 1:40:52.458
The main thing though, is that
it's first-rate work and has a future.

1:40:52.541 --> 1:40:53.958
And so do you.

1:40:54.041 --> 1:40:56.708
I'll call you later with some thoughts,
if that's okay.

1:40:56.791 --> 1:40:58.833
Meanwhile, be proud.

1:41:00.750 --> 1:41:02.041
[clicks]

1:41:30.958 --> 1:41:34.791
You know, there was a small--
very, very small piece of me

1:41:34.875 --> 1:41:39.000
that was the teensiest bit happy
to hear you're not leaving.

1:41:39.791 --> 1:41:42.166
I'd have been sad not
to see you every Sunday morning.

1:41:42.250 --> 1:41:43.458
Oh. Cheers.

1:41:44.208 --> 1:41:47.375
I told Freddy.
He's pissed off at your agent.

1:41:47.458 --> 1:41:50.208
-[both chuckle]
-How is he?

1:41:51.000 --> 1:41:53.291
-He should be going home soon.
-Really?

1:41:53.375 --> 1:41:55.583
Yes. Yes. [laughing]

1:41:55.666 --> 1:41:58.666
-[glasses clink]
-[whispers] God…

1:42:07.916 --> 1:42:08.958
Oh.

1:42:16.375 --> 1:42:18.875
-Uh, I'll be-- Yeah.
-You go handle that.

1:42:20.333 --> 1:42:21.458
[entry bell chimes]

1:42:22.833 --> 1:42:24.375
-Hi.
-Hi.

1:42:24.458 --> 1:42:25.791
I didn't know you were, um…

1:42:25.875 --> 1:42:29.000
I wasn't sure whether
you would want me here.

1:42:30.666 --> 1:42:32.000
[chuckles lightly]

1:42:33.166 --> 1:42:34.583
I'm so happy you're here.

1:42:36.958 --> 1:42:39.708
So how was the reading? Did anybody--?

1:42:44.916 --> 1:42:48.083
-I'm sorry.
-No, it's okay.

1:42:51.083 --> 1:42:54.000
-I really wanted to be there. I just--
-Susan…

1:42:55.916 --> 1:42:57.125
I know.

1:43:02.041 --> 1:43:03.708
What are you gonna do now?

1:43:05.958 --> 1:43:07.291
I'm gonna start the next one.

1:43:13.041 --> 1:43:14.583
I decided to take the job.

1:43:17.541 --> 1:43:18.541
[softly] Okay.

1:43:22.958 --> 1:43:24.083
I'm happy for you.

1:43:28.250 --> 1:43:29.583
Happy birthday.

1:43:32.583 --> 1:43:33.666
Thank you.

1:43:34.875 --> 1:43:37.416
You really didn't have to get me anything.

1:43:49.250 --> 1:43:50.833
It's for the next one.

1:43:54.208 --> 1:43:55.750
Got any ideas?

1:43:59.791 --> 1:44:01.000
Just questions.

1:44:02.666 --> 1:44:04.833
That seems like
a really good place to start.

1:44:16.000 --> 1:44:17.375
Goodbye, Jonathan.

1:44:25.958 --> 1:44:29.041
[Susan] The next one was tick, tick… BOOM!

1:44:29.125 --> 1:44:34.083
After that, he went back to a project
he'd started and put away, called Rent.

1:44:35.708 --> 1:44:38.375
It ran on Broadway for 12 years.

1:44:40.041 --> 1:44:43.125
It changed the definition
of what a musical could be.

1:44:44.333 --> 1:44:46.291
What it could sound like.

1:44:47.416 --> 1:44:49.583
The kinds of stories it could tell.

